<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Traffic Deaths Falling to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The number of pedestrians and
bicyclists killed by drivers in New York City declined toward a record
low, according to a report of the New York Times Monday.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary police records show that from January 1 to June 3
of this year, 71 pedestrians and bicyclists were killed by motor
vehicles -- a 36 percent drop from the same period in 1997, in which
111 were killed.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the city authorities have vigorously pushed traffic
enforcement as a means to make New York City safer. They instructed
the police to erect pedestrian barricades, hand out more speeding
tickets, discourage jaywalking and install new signs informing drivers
that the speed limit is 30 miles per hour in most places.
</P>
<P>
Now, it appears that those efforts are beginning to pay off.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that the number of pedestrians and bicyclists
killed in the city this year would be about 168 -- which would be
significantly lower than the previous low of 245 in 1996, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, traffic deaths for pedestrians and bicyclists stood at
365. Then came a drop that has since leveled off at around 250 deaths.
</P>
<P>
The city's efforts in cracking down traffic deaths are in varied
forms. In March, the city unveiled a much-publicized "zero tolerance" day,
in which police officers used hand-held radar guns and unmarked
cruisers to catch speeding drivers, and installed more than 1,100 new
signs informing drivers of the speed limit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
