<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes to Continue Strong Relations with Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States hopes to
continue its strong relations with Japan despite resignation of
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto following a defeat of his party
in the Japanese Upper House election, the White House said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Mike McCurry said President Bill Clinton was
expected to take a call from Hashimoto late on Monday evening in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
He said U.S. officials would work with Japanese officials to
schedule a visit by the new prime minister. Hashimoto was
scheduled to pay a state visit to the United States later this
month, but the trip was canceled as a result of Hashimoto's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
McCurry also said Washington hoped a newly formed Japanese
government would take quick action on economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
"It is very important to the United States that new
government, whatever its composition, move quickly to implement
concrete fiscal and banking measures to achieve strong domestic
demand-led growth in Japan and to restore confidence in Japan's
financial system," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We think they will see it in their own self-interest to
pursue economic reform quickly," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
