<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Russia Confirm to Execute Missile Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot and Russian presidents
have confirmed the two sides' readiness to go ahead with the
implementation of a deal for the delivery of Russian-made S-300
surface-to-air missile system to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The confirmation was made in a meeting between Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides and his Russian counterpart Boris
Yeltsin in the Kremlin Monday, Cyprus News Agency (CNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Clerides is currently in Moscow to be a guest of honor at the
opening of the World Youth Games to be held in the Russian
capital, at the invitation of Moscow Mayor Yury Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
CNA quoted Yeltsin's aide Sergei Prikhodko as saying after the
meeting that "it was confirmed what had been repeatedly agreed -
the two parties' readiness to honor the earlier assumed
obligations" relating to the delivery of the missile system to the
Greek Cypriots-controlled southern part.
</P>
<P>
Prikhodko noted that military and technical cooperation
between Russia and Cyprus "is an integral part of our inter-state
relations."
</P>
<P>
However, he did not say when the delivery will take place. A
week ago, Russian officials said that Moscow had decided to delay
delivery of the missiles until late this fall.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed the missile contract with Russian manufacturers
in January 1997. The 425-million-U.S.-dollar deal includes
launchers and missiles, together with long-range guidance radars,
which could be deployed on the divided island late this summer.
</P>
<P>
The deal has angered Turkish Cypriots, who resided in the
northern part of the divided island and their ally Turkey, who
said their security would be seriously endangered by the missiles
that have a range of 150 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has vowed to take all necessary measures to prevent the
deployment of the missiles on the island, which threatens an armed
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Russia has supported Clerides' proposal for demilitarization of
the island as precondition for cancellation of the missile deal.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the meeting between the two presidents, Prikhodko
said there was identity of views on the prospects and ways to
solve the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries expressed their desire to strengthen
even further economic relations.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
aftermath of a abortive coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
