<HEADLINE> Zabel Takes Over Yellow Jersey as Boardman Crashes Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- German Erik Zabel took advantage of
Briton Chris Boardman's sudden fall to pick up the leader's yellow
jersey after the second stage of the Tour de France reached in
Cork of Ireland on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Zabel gained 12 seconds in time bonuses at three intermediate
sprints to take the overall lead minutes after the British rider
had fallen 57 kms from the end of the 205.5-km leg from
Enniscorthy.
</P>
<P>
Czech Jan Svorada won the stage by sprinting clear of
Australian Robbie McEwen with Italy's Mario Cipollini third as the
riders finished an hour behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
Boardman was taken out of the race on the orders of Tour doctor
Gerard Porte after suffering a deep cut above an eye.
</P>
<P>
"He was really groggy and he couldn't remember crashing so I
withdrew him," said Porte. 
</P>
</TEXT>
