<HEADLINE> Israel Denies Training Turkish Pilots to Destroy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli government on Monday
strongly denied reports that Israel has trained Turkish fighter
pilots to destroy anti-aircraft missiles to be deployed by Cyprus,
saying their relations do not target at any third party.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry spokesman dismissed as "baseless" the
reports on a Turkish newspaper, which also said that a military
base has been set up in southern Turkey for Israel to use.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted the spokesman as saying that Israel and
Turkey have stated more than once that the relations between the
two countries are "not aimed at another party."
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post reported Monday that in a sign of strong
military relations between Israel and Turkey, Turkey has decided
to increase the number of military attaches in Israel from one to
three.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also quoted a senior Israeli airforce commander
as confirming that a squadron of Turkish fighter jets were
training in Negev of southern Israel three weeks ago. But the
commander declined to say what type of training they were doing.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been criticized by Arab and Muslim countries, as
well as its Mediterranean rival Greece, for its military
cooperation with Israel, which includes joint military exercises
and training of Turkish pilots in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post quoted the Jane's Defense Weekly as
reporting that Turkey is continuing with contingency plans for
taking military action against the Greek-Cypriots should they
deploy the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed the missile contract with Russian manufacturers
in January 1997. The 425-million-U.S.-dollar deal includes
launchers and missiles, together with long-range guidance radars,
which could be deployed on the divided island late this summer.
</P>
<P>
The deal has angered Turkish Cypriots, who resided in the
northern part of the divided island and their ally Turkey, who
said their security would be seriously endangered by the missiles
that have a range of 150 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has vowed to take all necessary measures to prevent the
deployment of the missiles on the island, which threatens an armed
confrontation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
