<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Reveals EU Presidency Work Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Enlargement negotiation and
Kosovo crisis are high on the work program Austria revealed on
Monday for its rotating presidency of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schussel detailed the work
program before fellow foreign ministers from EU member states at
Monday's general affairs council.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that nothing will serve the objective of political
stability and economic progress in Europe better than the
integration of European Union's neighbors into the union and that
hardly any other country has as great an interest in the success
of enlargement as Austria that shares borders with four candidate
countries for accession.
</P>
<P>
Schussel said that the six-month Austrian presidency wants to
open substantive negotiations with candidates countries.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has invited Poland, Hungary, the Czech
Republic, Romania, Slovenia and Cyprus to start accession talks.
</P>
<P>
Austria also promised to continue stressing employment that was
the highlight during the Luxembourg presidency in the latter half
of last year as well as the transition to the realization of the
single currency, euro.
</P>
<P>
As for external relations, the Austrian foreign minister rated
Kosovo high on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
He said that the EU foreign ministers had started to
concentrate on the status of the Yugoslav province and that what
EU aims for is a status the Kosovars will agree to so as to remain
within the borders of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"We have to be careful in that any changes of geographical
borders in that area might have spillover or domino effects," he
told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
When asked how to work out the difference between the culture
autonomy offered by Belgrade and the outright independence strived
for by the Liberation Army of Kosovo, Schussel said that it will
be a difficult task in that different people have differing
understandings about the term autonomy.
</P>
<P>
But the Austrian presidency made it clear that the first
priority in Kosovo is to stop all acts of violence as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
The EU will maintain its pressure on Belgrade for it to fulfil
its international obligations but will also apply pressure on the
inhabitants of Kosovo as "a growing radicalisation can be
detected".
</P>
<P>
The Austrian presidency will also continue the union's role in
peace-making in the Middle East, Schussel added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
