<HEADLINE> Iran Expresses Regrets Over Escalation of War in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran's special representative on
Afghanistan Alaeddin Boroujerdi Monday voiced Tehran's regret over
the escalation of war in Afghanistan after the Taliban militia
captured a key city from the anti-Taliban Northern Alliance on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Denouncing the Taliban offensive as "fratricide," Boroujerdi
said experience has shown that the ups and downs in military
ground have no impact on the major principle to put an end to the
Afghan crisis through political means.
</P>
<P>
Winning victory through wars is an injustice against the Afghan
people who are suffering from the atrocities of war, the official
news agency IRNA quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim military group Taliban forces took over Maimana,
capital city of the northwestern Faryab province, after heavy
fighting with opposition forces loyal to the Uzbek General Abdul
Rashid Dostam.
</P>
<P>
Faryab was a major stronghold of Dostam, who joined the
Northern Alliance after the Taliban militia ousted the government
of President Burhanuddin Rabbani in September, 1996.
</P>
<P>
He underlined the importance of the peacemaking efforts of the
United Nations, the Organization of the Islamic Conference and the
regional states, expressing the hope that political negotiations
would replace military operations in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
During a visit of Pakistani special envoy Iftakhar Murshid to
Tehran last week, Iran and Pakistan, two influential neighbors of
Afghanistan, agreed to continue joint efforts to push forward the
Afghan deadlocked peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
