<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Confidence in UK at Five-year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Business confidence in Britain is
at its lowest for at least five years, according to a survey
published on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The survey of more than 1,400 finance and managing directors
was carried out between June 10 and June 26, shortly after the
Bank of England's monetary policy committee raised interest rates
to 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Philip Mellor, senior analyst from Dun &AMP; Bradstreet, an
information service which conducted the survey, said: "These
results partially reflect the first flush of pessimism in the wake
of the news about increased inflation and interest rates. They
show a significant downturn in economic confidence."
</P>
<P>
"As more and more firms expect further increases in interest
rates, so business gloom has spread from exporters into the
domestic economy," he added.
</P>
<P>
A separate report, published by Oxford Economic Forecasting
(OEF), said that Britain faced the potential problem of
stagflation with a combination of rising wage inflation and a
beleaguered manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
It said that there was every chance that the Bank of England
would raise interest rates further, increasing the risk of a hard
landing for the economy.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for the economy depends in part on the Bank's
response to any further weakening in sterling. It would be wrong
to defend a pound under pressure from weakening economic growth by
raising rates, OEF argued.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
