<HEADLINE> Saudi King Welcomes Palestine's New U.N. Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz
on Monday welcomed the decision by the United Nations General
Assembly to upgrade the status of the Palestinian observer
delegation.
</P>
<P>
King Fahd made his statement during the weekly session of the
Saudi cabinet held under his chairmanship, according to the Saudi
Press Agency (SPA).
</P>
<P>
SPA said that the king regarded the U.N. decision as "a
positive step on the right path towards full membership for the
Palestinian state" in the international organization.
</P>
<P>
Brushing aside objections by the United States and Israel, the
U.N. General Assembly voted overwhelmingly on July 7 to upgrade
the status of the Palestinian observer mission in the U.N. to
nonvoting seat.
</P>
<P>
This gives Palestine the right to participate in the general
debate, a three-week-long litany of political speeches at the
opening of the General Assembly in the fall of the year.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolution also gives Palestine the right to speak on
any subject, not just the Middle East to which it had been
restricted under the old formula.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian delegation will also be able to co-sponsor
resolutions on Palestinian and Middle East issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
