<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Complains About Illegal Employment of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The rampancy of illegal hiring of
Filipinos in Jordan have induced these people to low salary,
abuse and inability of returning to the motherland, the Philippine
Embassy here said.
</P>
<P>
Some 7,000 Filipinos are currently working in the kingdom and
only half of them hold valid contracts approved by the Jordanian
Ministry of Interior and authenticated by the Philippine Embassy,
the embassy said in a press release obtained Monday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Filipinos illegally employed in Jordan are
household workers and they are usually paid less than 300
U.S. dollars a month, which the Philippine labor regulations
define as the minimum salary for a household worker, exclusive of
food and accommodation.
</P>
<P>
Besides low payment, in recent years there have been some
reports of sexual, physical and psychological abuses against some
of the three million Filipinos working overseas, especially those
in the Gulf countries, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The same thing happened to the Filipinos illegally working in
Jordan, although it is not so problematic, it added.
</P>
<P>
Because of their illegal identity, the Filipinos have to bear
anything that the employers exert on them, even physical and
psychological abuses, it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there are now a lot of Filipinos in Jordan unable to
leave the kingdom because they can not afford long-overdue fees.
</P>
<P>
Some employers did not help their Philippine household workers
apply for extension of visas after they finished the
contracts. Any foreigner in Jordan alone can not apply for such an
extension. He will be charged one Jordanian dinar (about 1.4
dollars) for each day he overstays his visas.
</P>
<P>
The embassy admitted in its press release that a five-year
closure of the Philippine Embassy in Jordan from 1993 to 1998
created many problems for the Filipinos working in the kingdom and
resulted in the mushrooming of illegal agencies recruiting workers
directly from the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
According to the labor law enforced in 1996 in the
Philippines, Filipinos can only be recruited through direct
hiring from their motherland and Philippine household workers can
only be employed by the Jordanian Royal family, cabinet
ministers, other high officials in the Jordanian government and
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
However, illegal agencies in Jordan have not respected the
labor law and made Filipinos hired by anyone who wanted and
afforded to do so while not giving valid contracts and not
applying governmental permission for them, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The embassy hoped the Jordanian government to agree to issue a
special amnesty for workers who were hired illegally and can not
pay the fees for over-staying.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government has placed the total number of guest
workers in the kingdom at over half a million and has long tried
to regulate foreign employment and reduce the number of illegal
aliens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official Calls for Arab Solidarity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian Official
Monday called on Arab countries to enhance cooperation and
soldiarity in order to reactivate the stalled peace process in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Farouk Kadoumy, head of the Palestinian Liberation
Organization's Political Department, made the appeal in a news
conference jointly held with Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz.
</P>
<P>
According to the Lebanese National News Agency, Kadoumy said
all Arab negotiations with Israel are connected and therefore
solidarity between Arab countries are needed in order to gain a
stronger bargaining position.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed the necessity of convening an Arab summit to
formulate a new Arab strategy aimed at countering Israel's
intransigency in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
He said that Jerusalem, a holy city both Israel and Palestine
claimed as their capital, is not only for Palestine, but for all
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian track in the peace process is currently
stalled as Israel refuses to accept a United States initiative for
an Israeli withdrawal from 13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz said Israel is attempting to empty all peace accords
signed with Arabs, and at the same time projects itself to the
world as a peace-seeker.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese foreign minister called on the U.S. to play a fair
and honest role in the peace talks and pressure Israel to keep its
promises made toward Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Kadoumy came to Lebanon Saturday on a three-day visit after
winding up a trip to Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
