<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Direct Investment in and by OECD Countries in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) said on Monday that despite the
financial crisis in Asia, the direct investment in and by OECD
countries broke record in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The direct investment by OECD countries attained 355 billion
U.S. dollars, 19 percent more than 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, these countries received 255 billion U.S. dollars
worth of direct investment, 16 percent more than 1996, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Direct investment is considered the best there is by all
governments, because of their stable capitals, jobs created from
them and technological transfers.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain were on top of the 29 OECD
countries in making and receiving direct investments in 1996, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
However, direct investment in and by France dropped by 12
billion U.S. dollars as compared with 1996, with 14.8 billion U.S.
dollars of investment by foreign enterprises in France and 24.9
billion U.S. dollars of investment made by France abroad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Sees Growing need for International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- There is a growing need for
international arrangements, treaties or institutions to deal with
those "problems without passport", U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive written interview with Xinhua News Agency,
Annan said, "Increasingly, we live in a global village. The Asian
economic crisis, for example, is being felt around the world. And
the world must devise a solution which requires international
mechanisms, such as the International Monetary Fund."
</P>
<P>
"So whether we are talking about financial stability,
depletion of the ozone layer, the fight against AIDS or the
need to control drug trafficking, I see a growing need for
international agreements, treaties or institutions to deal with
these problems without passports," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Annan believed the the United Nations, the world's only universal
organization, would take the lead in the next century to
tackle these problems.
</P>
<P>
"To do so effectively, the United Nations will have to focus
its energies on those areas where it can contribute most," Annan
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Population Growth Rate Drops to 1.41 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran's population growth rate has
dropped to 1.41 percent at present from 1.56 percent in 1996,
Deputy Health Minister Ali Akbar Sayari announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to local press on the occasion of World Population
Day which fell last Saturday, Sayari warned that family planning
is still a serious issue in Iran since 1.2 million new-born
children add to the population every year.
</P>
<P>
The evening daily Kayhan quoted him as saying that at present
24 percent of pregnancies are still unwanted in the country. And
because of a lack of education, 50 percent of women receiving
private services and 27 percent of women receiving public services
are using contraceptives in wrong ways.
</P>
<P>
He said that at present 50 percent of married people are using
modern family planning methods while 20 percent of them are using
traditional means.
</P>
<P>
Sayari did not mention the country's population. But earlier
official report put the figure at 60,055,488 in 1996 with 61
percent living in urban areas and 39 percent in rural regions.
</P>
<P>
Iran's population growth rate stood as high as 3.2 percent
during the decade between 1976 and 1986. But after the economic
hardships in the 1990s, more and more Iran people have abandoned
the tradition to have a large family. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on Foreign Aid for Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- If the rich-poor gap is
going to close, developing countries have to be plugged in to the
global economy and to compete internationally, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive written interview with Xinhua News Agency,
Annan said the foreign assistance has been in the trend of
declining for years, and foreign investment, on the other hand,
has been increasing.
</P>
<P>
Annan said private companies today have not only the capital,
but also the technology and the management skills that developing
countries need.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the primary goal for the United Nations is to assist
developing countries to structure their laws and their economies
in a way to make them more attractive to private investors.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed that for many countries or regions, particularly
in Africa, establishing political stability is the first
requirement to develop their economies.
</P>
<P>
In this global village, every member benefits when one member
is made stronger and economically more viable and prosperous, the
U.N. chief added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
