<HEADLINE> Turkey Denies Reported Israeli Use of Airbase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Ministry here
Monday denied allegations in news reports that a military airbase
being constructed in eastern Turkey has been used by Israeli for
spy purposes.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the ministry called "totally baseless and
intentional" the claims that Israel used the military airbase in
eastern Turkey and conducted espionage activities against
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The news reports first appeared in the Christian Science
Monitor newspaper and later in the Turkish press, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
"Despite all the denials, several circles are still trying to
spread these (claims). It is clear that recent news reports in
this respect which appeared in the media is a continuation of
these allegations," added the statement.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel are developing bilateral ties for "the
benefit of the peoples of the two countries and have no objectives
aimed at a third country," it said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel have signed a series of military and defense
accords under which they share airspace and bases for training
purposes.
</P>
<P>
The rapidly expanding Turkish-Israeli military cooperation has
prompted serious concern among Arab countries, who fear it would
change the region's balance of power. 
</P>
