<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A shipment of U.S. wheat ordered by the Jordanian
Ministry of Supply arrived at Jordan's Red Sea port of Aqaba on
Sunday, Jordan's official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
The import of the 50,000 tonnes of U.S. wheat is part of the
ministry's plan to secure a strategic storage of wheat for human
consumption, according to the news agency.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) President Sheikh
Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan Sunday issued a decree to approve the
state budget of the 1998 fiscal year, the UAE News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The budget envisages an expenditure of 21.393 billion dirhams
(5.85 billion U.S. dollars) and revenues of 19.635 billion dirhams
(5.36 billion dollars), with the deficit hitting 1.758 billion
dirhams (480 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The state budget was approved by the Federal National Council
(Parliament) in March.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus announced Monday that it has reached an
agreement with Israel to cooperate in installing a submarine fiber
optic cable system.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus Telecommunications Authority, the cable
linking Israel, Cyprus and Italy would began operation at the
beginning of next year.
</P>
<P>
The landing points will be Tel Aviv of Israel, Yeroskipou of
Cyprus and Mazara of Italy.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus would participate in the system through the Israeli MED1
Submarine Cable Ltd. company, which has undertaken the cable's
construction, operation and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is considered as one of the major steps that
Cyprus takes to reinforce its role as a regional
telecommunications hub. 
</P>
</TEXT>
