<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Calls for Ease of Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot government spokesman
Christos Stylianides Monday called for solution to the Cyprus
problem, saying the demilitarization of the island is the way to
reduce tension on this Eastern Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
He made the call while commenting on a report in Turkish daily
"Hurriyet" Monday that six F-16 Turkish fighters have conducted
exercises at an Israeli training center, designed to destroy the
Russian-made S-300 missile defense system, expected to be deployed
on the island later this year.
</P>
<P>
"Cyprus' demilitarization and the solution of the Cyprus
problem is the only way the tension that Turkey is trying to
create in the region could be tackled," the spokesman said at his
press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Turkish press reports, Stylianides said he
had no information on the issue. Cyprus "has always maintained a
cautious stance toward the military defense agreement between
Israel and Turkey," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that Israel has reassured the Cypriot
government that its agreement with Turkey does not affect Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Cypriot government is investigating into
the reports about Turkish military aircraft training exercises in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
But the Israeli Embassy in Cyprus Monday denied the Turkish
press reports that Turkish military planes conducted exercises in
Israel with the purpose to destroy the Russian-made missiles
purchased by Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the Israeli Embassy "categorically denies
these reports" and described them as "unfounded and untrue."
</P>
<P>
"The embassy also denied the reports that an air-base will be
built in eastern Turkey, that will be especially used by Israeli
planes," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government ordered the S-300 missiles from Russia
in January 1997 to boost its defense. The deal angered Turkey and
the Turkish Cypriots, who fear that their security will be
seriously endangered by the missiles that have a range of 150
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has vowed to take all necessary measures to prevent the
deployment of the missiles on the island.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz warned last week that his
country would bring missiles to the occupied northern areas if the
Cypriot government goes ahead with the deployment of the missiles.
</P>
<P>
If the missiles are deployed, "tension will increase in Cyprus
and an armed conflict could arise, and we won't be the losers,"
Yilmaz said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkey landed and
took over the northern third of the island in 1974 after a
short-lived Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in the north, recognized
only by Turkey, which maintains 35,000 troops there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Defends France's 1994 Intervention in Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Monday implicitly defended France's 1994 military intervention in
Rwanda as purely humanitarian instead of an interference into the
internal affairs of that central African state.
</P>
<P>
"Some critics ask about the real aims and situation of the
engagement of our forces outside our national territory. But the
foreign residents evacuated last year from Brazzaville, or the
people of Sarajevo in suffering, know with what kind of courage
and what self-sacrifice our soldiers rescued them," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
He made the declaration during a traditional meeting with
military and civilian officials of the defense ministry on the eve
of the French National Day.
</P>
<P>
But Chirac did not mention the name of Rwanda or the exact
military operation France launched in 1994 in that country.
</P>
<P>
"France does not seek to interfere into the internal affairs of
other countries. She tries to protect the people, to maintain
peace and allow the rules of international laws be respected," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The French National Assembly has been holding hearings over the
past six months on the role France played before and during the
1994 genocide committed by the Hutu majority against Tutsi
minority in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Some critics have accused France of supporting the Hutu
military regime of Rwanda before the genocide took place.
</P>
</TEXT>
