<HEADLINE> House Prices Rise in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- House prices in South Africa
increased further in the second quarter of the year, the ABSA
banking group announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Allied Bank of South Africa (ABSA) said the increase was
caused by market instability, the depreciation of the Rand, and
the subsequent increase in interest rates and bond rates.
</P>
<P>
"Volatile financial markets look certain to force interest
rates and bond rates to remain on high levels for an indefinite
period, negatively affecting the house market in the process,"
ABSA said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The highest house price rise was recorded in the Northern Cape
province (27.7 percent) and the lowest in Gauteng (9.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
Building costs of new houses rose by an average of 15.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
The mortgage rate stands between 21.50 and 22 percent at
present. 
