<HEADLINE> Israeli Inner Cabinet Fails to Decide on Pullback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli inner cabinet Monday
failed again to make a decision on the second redeployment of
Israeli troops in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of Israel Radio, Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu hold talks with other three inner cabinet members for
about one hour in an effort to reach a consensus over the next
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the three members - Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon and Trade and
Industry Minister Natan Sharansky - agreed with Netanyahu to
continue talks on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Early on Monday, Netanyahu said that Israel "almost closed the
gaps" with the United States over the long-overdue pullback issue,
which remained a major obstacle to a revival of peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the only thing holding up the progress is
the Palestinian refusal to implement their commitments to fight
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been stalled for over a
year over the extent of the next Israeli withdrawal in the West
Bank. A U.S. initiative calls on Israel to hand over 13 percent
more of the West Bank in return for the fulfillment of the
Palestinian commitments.
</P>
<P>
The right-wing in the Israeli government opposed to the
proposed scope, saying it would endanger the security interests of
Israel. The hawkish leader Sharon also noted that any redeployment
of more than 9 percent would not be acceptable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
