<HEADLINE> Uganda's Top Legislator Named As Ruling Party's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Parliament Speaker James
Wapakhabulo was elected as the National Political Commissar (NPC)
of the ruling National Resistance Movement (NRM) Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
President Yoweri Museveni, who was elected unopposed as the
chairperson of the NRM Monday morning, proposed to the NRM's
National Executive Committee two candidates for the post.
</P>
<P>
The 113-member committee chose the Speaker after the other
candidate stepped down at the last minute in favor of
Wapakhabulo.
</P>
<P>
In his brief speech as the NPC, Wapakhabulo pledged to make
the permanent secretariat of the Movement an effective and
efficient organ and to provide through political schools
qualified cadres for the Movement branches throughout Uganda.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned the delegates that the people of Uganda will
judge the Movement through its performance in creating jobs,
eliminating poverty, providing health, education and building
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
He promised to carry out frequent inspections to see how well
the Movement performs in these and other important areas to
ensure that the Movement remains relevant and popular.
</P>
<P>
The Speaker's success in handling the controversial
constituent assembly which debated and enacted the 1995
constitution shot him to political stardom. He then was elected
unopposed as MP for eastern Mbale Municipality and subsequently
Speaker.
</P>
<P>
Under the Constitution of Uganda, the Speaker is the third in
the hierarchy after the President and Vice President.
</P>
<P>
The NPC, also deemed as the number three within the Movement,
is often depicted as the most active. He is mainly responsible
for mobilization and other important matters within the ruling
party.
</P>
<P>
The national congress of the NRM has drawn 1,554 delegates
from all over the country and is to end Friday. It is the first
of its kind in Uganda's history and is to be held every five
years.
</P>
<P>
President Museveni has been holding the chair of the Movement
since it took power in 1986. This time the chairperson, vice
chairperson and national political commissar are elected to run a
five-year term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
