<HEADLINE> S. Africa, EU to Resume Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A new round of free trade
negotiations between South Africa and the European Union (EU)
will resume in Pretoria Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The EU is expected to table an improved offer in response to
concessions made by South Africa in last month's Brussels talks.
</P>
<P>
South Africa proposed to increase its offer to cover 85
percent of imports from the EU that would have duty-free access
to the South African market, conditional upon the EU revising its
offer to cover at least 95 percent of products from South Africa,
South African Press Association reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The EU is under pressure to achieve a trade agreement with
South Africa by October this year following EU leaders' pledge to
South African President Nelson Mandela at the EU summit in
Cardiff, Wales last month.
</P>
<P>
The South African negotiating team will be headed by its
ambassador to the EU, Elias Links, and the EU's by Philip Lowe,
its director-general in charge of development.
</P>
<P>
Michael Laidler, EU ambassador to South Africa, said Monday
that both sides had been working at improving the proposed trade
deal.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident the offers have been improved on both sides. The
point is to try and continue to improve them."
</P>
<P>
Laidler could not say whether this week's talks would be
definitive, but stressed there was no standoff in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"We are making steady progress," he said.
</P>
<P>
A South African trade official said Monday that the talks would
cover all outstanding issues of customs cooperation and the rules of
origin of products. 
</P>
