<HEADLINE> Child Malnutrition Grows in Sudan City: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A set of nutritional surveys
recently conducted by the U.N. found that more than half of the
children in war-torn southern Sudan's Bahr el Ghazal province are
malnourished, the Operation Lifeline Sudan (OLS) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Around 4,000 of the children are estimated to require
therapeutic feeding, OLS, the coordinator of U.N. efforts to
assist Sudan said in a statement it issued jointly with the U.N.
Children Fund (UNICEF) here.
</P>
<P>
In order to meet the needs of 38,000 children in Bahr el
Ghazal, OLS said it requires four million U.S. Dollars to open
another 19 feeding centers.
</P>
<P>
At present, OLS is feeding almost 14,000 children in 19
feeding centers. Plans are underway to double the figures
following the surveys.
</P>
<P>
The major reason for the high rates of child malnutrition is
lack of food rather than prevalence of disease, said Ted Chaiban,
Deputy Chief of Operations of the U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
"During this time of year, the 'hunger gap', rates of child
malnutrition are always high. This year, however, we are seeing a
significant increase over last year's already high figure of 40
percent child malnutrition," he said.
</P>
<P>
Civil war in southern Sudan has entered the 15th year between
the Moslem-led Khartoum government and the rebel Sudan People's
Liberation Army fighting for more autonomy in the animist and
Christian-dominated south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
