<HEADLINE> Somali Capital Cleared of Road blocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Mogadishu sighed with relief
after security campaigns have been launched Monday by organized
armed militiamen on the road between Mogadishu and Afgoie, 30 km
south of the capital, and the main streets linking it.
</P>
<P>
The two main operations which coincided have cleared dozens of
road blocks which made those streets hardly passable for the
public transport buses in the past.
</P>
<P>
More than 17 illegal road blocks were removed from the
Mogadishu-Afgoie road by forces loyal to Hussein Ali Weheliye
Erfo, the chief security person of lower Shabelle Region Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was prompted by outrageous activities carried out
by freelance militiamen who collected extortion money from the
public transport vehicles going from Mogadishu to Afgoie and the
other way round.
</P>
<P>
Many bus owners had put their vehicles in garages after they
found out that the profit they were making did not correspond to
the extortion money they were asked by the militiamen.
</P>
<P>
The relief has also been observed in the northern part of
Mogadishu after the public transport buses have once again
started operating Monday following a serious protest by the
drivers early Sunday in which the buses had stopped crossing from
the north to the south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
All people went on foot Sunday to cross the former green lines
to conduct their routine businesses since no buses had operated
because of the protest against the road blocks.
</P>
<P>
The security operation in northern Mogadishu has been carried
out by Ali Sheikh Mohamud (Sheikh Ali Dhere), the former chairman
of North Mogadishu's collapsed Islamic courts, and his militiamen
who rounded up more than 11 freelance gunmen.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 illegal road blocks have been erected by outlawed
militiamen in the main streets linking the former north and south
parts of the capital where they forced bus drivers to pay 5,000
Shillings (nearly 65 U.S. Cents), a considerably high extortion
money, for each trip they cross from the North to the South of
the capital city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
