<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Rejects Portugal's Position on G. Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) has rejected the request by Portugal that
it should steer clear of the Guinea Bissau conflict, the official
News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
NAN quoted Lansana Kouyate, Executive Secretary of ECOWAS as
saying at the weekend in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso that
Portugal's request is unacceptable to the regional body.
</P>
<P>
He said though Guinea Bissau is a former Portugal territory,
it is in West Africa and therefore, shares same geographical
experiences, adding that "colonial era is over."
</P>
<P>
"If the former colonial master wants to assist in solving the
problems of its former territory, it must do so in concert with
the regional grouping where the territory is currently located,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, about a week ago, Portugal asked
ECOWAS not to intervene in its former territory's political
issues because it was going to step in together with Angola,
another former Portugal territory in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The president of Guinea Bissau is aware of the existence of
its former colonial master before it requested the ECOWAS
chairman to assist in quelling the conflict in his country,
Kouyate said.
</P>
<P>
Guinea Bissau President Joao Bernado Vieira had requested the
military intervention of the sub-regional peace-keeping force
ECOMOG in his country, following the rebellion led by former Army
Chief of Staff Amsumane Mane, who was sacked by Vieira in June
for neglect of duty.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS countries had met on his request and decided to use
dialog and negotiations, imposition of sanctions and enforcement
of embargo and use of force to resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kouyate said ECOWAS has also decided not to answer Portugal
because its request is not reasonable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
