<HEADLINE> W. Africa Has One Million Refugees: UNHCR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The current number of refugees in
west Africa has increased to about one million from 20,000 in
1989, according to the United Nations High Commission for
Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
The conflicts in Liberia, Sierra Leone, Senegal, Mali and
Mauritania were responsible for the rise in the number of
refugees in the region, UNHCR said in a publication reaching here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to it, the Liberian crisis triggered by the civil
war beginning 1989 produced 472,000 refugees, while 500,000
others were as a result of the Sierra Leonean conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, along with five others -- Angola, Burundi,
Eritrea, Sudan and Somalia -- were the "laboratory" which
produced the refugees in Africa, UNHCR said.
</P>
<P>
The publication said as at January 1998, out of 22.3 million
refugees handled by the U.N. refugee body, 7.2 million were in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
It said that 2.2 million of the refugees from Africa have
recently returned to their places of origin, while 1.5 million
others were displaced.
</P>
<P>
According to the publication, 411,500 refugees were from the
Somali conflicts, 346,000 others were products of the Sudanese
armed struggle, while Eritrea accounted for 321,000 refugees in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR figure also showed that Burundi produced 268,000 of the
refugees, while 100,000 refugees and 75,000 others were milled
from the conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo and Rwanda
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
