<HEADLINE> 2 Irish Peacekeepers Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Two Irish soldiers of the United
Nations peacekeeping force serving in south Lebanon were wounded
Monday night by Israeli shelling, Lebanon's Voice of the People
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The two, both from the Irish battalion within the U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL), were wounded when Israeli artillery
troops shelled the Hataida village in the central sector of the
Israeli occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
A gasoline station owned by a Lebanese was also heavily
damaged in the attack, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
A UNIFIL official told the radio that the two Irish soldiers,
one man and one woman, had been transferred to the hospital in
UNIFIL's headquarters in Naqoura near the Israeli northern border.
</P>
<P>
He added that the force was investigating the incident.
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-member UNIFIL, comprising contingents from nine
countries, was established in 1978 after Israel's first invasion
of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
It was designed to help restore peace and security across the
border between Lebanon and Israel and confirm the Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has been complaining that the force had been
ineffective in protecting its northern border from Lebanese
guerrillas' attack.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' attack.
</P>
<P>
But its occupation has been facing up a strong Lebanese
resistance movement spearheaded by the Iranian-backed Hezbollah,
or Party of God. 
</P>
</TEXT>
