<HEADLINE> Libya to Help Bring Stability to Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Libyan leader Col. Muammar Gaddafi
has promised to help to bring about stability to Sierra Leone, an
official in the west African country said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi gave the assurance to Sierra Leonean President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah during his recent visit to Libya, said Kabbah's
spokesman in the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan leader promised to leave no stone unturned in
assisting Sierra Leone, said the spokesman, quoted by a British
Broadcasting Corporation report monitored here.
</P>
<P>
President Kabbah has already returned from a visit to Libya,
the spokesman said, but he did not say when the visit took place.
</P>
<P>
As a direct aid, Gaddafi has given Sierra Leonean people rice
and petroleum products to assist them at the difficult period, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman refused to disclose the quantity of the rice and
petroleum products, but presidential sources said it amounted to
several ship loads.
</P>
<P>
During his recent tour, President Kabbah visited Saudi Arabia
and met with King Fahd Abeul-Aziz and other top Saudi officials,
including the executive officials of the Islamic Development Bank
(ISB).
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the ISB has given clearance to
re-start operations in Sierra Leone after international financial
institutions and banks withdrew from that country following the
military coup in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Before the coup, Saudi Arabia had funded the Freetown
Peninsula Road through the ISB with some 25 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
