<HEADLINE> Demobilization for Better Equipment: Museveni </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
said Monday morning that the recent demobilization plan is aimed
at arming the Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) with better
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The president made the explanation at the opening ceremony of
the national congress of the ruling National Resistance Movement
(NRM) which was held in the International Conference Center here.
</P>
<P>
He said a massive infantry is not good enough for handling
regional matters and therefore the size of the army should be
reduced to save money for the advanced equipment.
</P>
<P>
The armies of nearly all the neighboring countries are better
equipped than that in Uganda, he cautioned.
</P>
<P>
According to a New Vision's Monday report, 330 army veterans
have been listed on the demobilization project.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out in the report that because the UPDF is better
equipped than rebels, the thugs are changing from attacking the
army to attacking soft targets to discredit the government that
is not giving enough protection to its people.
</P>
<P>
The payment for the veterans would be delayed to ensure that
the army is re-equipped first. The security of the country takes
priority over payment of workers, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the reduction of the size of the army, the
government increased the defense spending by 26 percent in the
budget for 1998/1999 to modernize its armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's army falls into four divisions, with a total number
of some 37,000 servicemen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
