<HEADLINE> British Army Defuses Huge Car Bomb in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The British army experts defused a
500 lb (225 kg) car bomb outside a court house in the Northern
Irish town of Newry on Monday, police said.
</P>
<P>
An army bomb disposal expert dismantled the device in a
four-hour security operation after a telephoned warning.
</P>
<P>
No group had claimed responsibility so far, but police said
dissident republicans were believed to be behind the car bomb
plot.
</P>
<P>
Police said the device, which contained home-made explosives,
was in the boot of a car parked on a street at the entrance to the
court.
</P>
<P>
It was the second bomb defused in the area since the parade
crisis started eight days ago -- on Sunday a 1,400 lb (645 kg)
device was found and dismantled by police on a builder's trailer
left on a road in nearby County Armagh.
</P>
<P>
The failed attack came during a day of tension in Northern
Ireland as thousands of the pro-British Protestant Orangemen held
parades in towns and villages to mark the high point of a
four-month "marching season".  
</P>
</TEXT>
