<HEADLINE> Peres Outlines Factors for Enliving Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon
Peres said here Monday that Jordan's King Hussein's efforts, the
U.S. participation and economic prosperity of Palestinians are the
three major factors for reviving the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Peres, who arrived here earlier Monday on a visit, made the
remark after meeting the king and exchanged views with him on the
current stalemate of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The role that was played and is still being played by Hussein
is very important for the establishment of peace in the region,
especially on the Palestinian-Israeli track," said Peres.
</P>
<P>
He asked Hussein to continue efforts to save the long-stalled
peace process, "otherwise it will be big loss for the whole
region."
</P>
<P>
The United States, as another side of the peace force, should
also continue to play its vital role in the Middle East, for its
participation is very important in maintaining peace and security
in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This requires intensifying the U.S. efforts to activate the
peace process, solve outstanding issues and ease tension in the
region," Peres added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Peres called on all the concerned sides to support
the Palestinians in achieving economic prosperity - another
important factor that can help revive the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Peres' visit came in a string of contacts between Jordan's
leadership and the prominent figures of the Israel's opposition
Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
Labor Knesset (parliament) member Yossi Beilin, who under the
government of late Yitzhak Rabin negotiated with the Palestinians
on peace accords, visited Amman late Sunday to pave the way for
Peres' visit.
</P>
<P>
Crown Prince Hassan talked with Beilin for an hour on the
latest developments of the Middle East peace process in light of
the U.S. proposal which calls for Israel to withdraw from 13.1
percent of the West Bank. The Palestinians have accepted the plan
while Israel rejected it.
</P>
<P>
In another development of the Israeli-Jordanian contacts, Labor
Party leader Ehud Barak is also due here Tuesday for talks with
Hussein and the crown prince.
</P>
<P>
These contacts are part of the efforts exerted by the Labor
party as well as by Jordan to push forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
