<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Helps Albania Collect Lost Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has
recommended that Albania improve its legal system and encourage
voluntary surrender instead of employing cash incentives to
collect weapons taken by civilians in the 1997 financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Some 650,000 weapons, 20,000 tons of explosives and 1.5 billion
bullets were taken away from the country's military depots, said a
report released here Monday by a U.N. team.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Evaluation Mission to Albania, led by U.N.
Under-Secretary-General for Disarmament Affairs Jayantha
Dhanapala, visited Albania from June 11-14 at the request of the
Albanian government.
</P>
<P>
The team met with Albanian leaders and representatives of
international bodies, Dhanapala told the press.
</P>
<P>
The report found that those taking weapons away were mostly
investors in a failed financial scheme called the Piramids which
promised huge returns on investment.
</P>
<P>
Many of the 3.3 million inhabitants in the mountainous
Southeast European country sold their properties including
livestock and homes to buy the shares before the scheme was
bankrupt. When their dreams shattered, panic and chaos followed.
</P>
<P>
Since August 1997 the government has retrieved about 10 percent
of the weapons. About 25 percent to 30 percent of the weapons not
returned to the government may have been moved out of the country
in contraband activities.
</P>
<P>
Most of those still holding the arms are using them to trade
for money as a quarter to a third of them are unemployed, the U.N.
mission believed. Use by organized criminals accounted for about
10 percent, Dhanapala said.
</P>
<P>
He said cash incentives or buy-back schemes are not feasible as
the number of weapons in question is so large and if doing so it
would send out the wrong message that unauthorized weapons
possession is a lucrative activity.
</P>
<P>
Dhanapala said the U.N. approach consists of disarmament and
development aimed at providing practical benefits to villages and
communities when the advocacy campaign for voluntary surrender is
practiced in the context of high unemployment in Albania.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Development Program (UNDP) is studying a pilot program
in the heaviest weapons possession district of Gramshi, 200 km
south of the capital of Tirana.
</P>
<P>
With a population of about 50,000, Gramshi is estimated to
account for roughly 8 to 10 percent of the weapons held by
civilians nationwide. The UNDP-assisted program may create 2,000
jobs among other benefits to bring to locals.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has helped many countries in weapons collection
programs but the Albanian case is the first in which civilians are
involved, Dhanapala said, noting that international cooperation is
needed in the operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carbon Said to Be Clue to El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Scientists from Harvard
University said they have found a clue to El Nino's origin by
studying a coral reef near the Galapagos Islands.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest issue of Science, Thomas P. Guilderson
and Daniel P. Schrag of Harvard University came to the conclusion
after examining the coral's carbon content to get a historical
record of subsurface water temperatures in the eastern tropical
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Since 1976, El Nino has become more frequent and more intense,
spawning floods, droughts and other foul weather around the globe.
But the cause of El Nino, a warming in equatorial Pacific surface
waters, has remained a mystery.
</P>
<P>
U.S. scientists said they found carbon 14 levels jumped much
more abruptly than normal in 1976, suggesting that warmer
subsurface waters may have flowed upward, causing surface
temperatures to increase.
</P>
<P>
However, the scientists said why this occurred, and whether it
has any connection to global warming remains unknown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0057 </DOCNO>
