<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Ties With Cuban Exile Bomber </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department said
Monday that it had no relations for decades with a Cuban exile who
contended his efforts to depose Cuban President Fidel Castro by
violent means were financed by a U.S. group.
</P>
<P>
Luis Posada Carriles, who once worked for the Central
Intelligence Agency (CIA), told his story in a series of
interviews with The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Posada as saying that he organized a
series of bombings in Cuba last year at hotels, discos and
restaurants, killing an Italian tourist in September.
</P>
<P>
Posada, 70, who was trained in demolition and guerrilla warfare
by the CIA, said the bombings were supported by the anti-Castro
Cuban-American National Foundation in Miami.
</P>
<P>
"We have not had a relationship with this person in decades,"
State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"In general the United States has repeatedly and strongly
condemned violent activities carried out against Cuba, allegedly
supported by persons or groups based in the United States," Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. government has investigated and will continue to
investigate allegations and prosecute violations of U.S. law," he
added.
</P>
<P>
According to The New York Times, Posada said over the years,
Jorge Mas Canosa, founder of the Cuban-American National
Foundation, sent him more than 200,000 U.S. dollars for his
operations against the Cuban leader. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Supports Arafat on Palestinian Statehood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Egypt supports Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat's determination to establish a Palestinian
state no matter what result of negotiations with Israel, Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Their right to establish a state is an international right,"
Moussa said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Moussa is in Washington to strengthen strategic ties with the
United States and to discuss U.S. economic and military aid for
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel had already accepted a Palestinian state by
recognizing the Palestinians as a people and the PLO as their
representative. "That goes with it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Oslo agreement provides for that," he added, referring to
the 1993 accord that set up the peace talks between Israel and the
Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's position obviously differs with that of the United
States. The Clinton administration has said the issue of the
Palestinian statehood is the one that should be negotiated between
Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
It opposed the U.N. General Assembly decision to extend
recognition as a virtual state to the PLO while Egypt supported
that decision.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also blamed Israel for the stalemate in negotiations
with the Palestinians over a series of issues, including the
second phase of Israeli troops' withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The United States has proposed that Israel concedes a further
13 percent of territory from the West Bank to the Palestinians,
which, while accepted by Arafat, has been rejected by Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on the ground of security.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Israel's resistance to the U.S. proposal could only
lead to disaster, to violence.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times has reported that Israeli and U.S. officials
expected talks on the U.S. proposal on the Israeli withdrawal from
the West Bank to be concluded by the end of July. But Moussa said
he did not believe Israel and the Palestinians could reach a peace
deal by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think so. We have heard that several times before," he
said. "The gap is still wide.... I don't think in that period of
time it will be possible to reach agreement." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
