<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Exports Goods Via Dire Dawa to Djibouti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Domestic products worth about
23 million U.S. Dollars are being exported via Dire Dawa to
Djibouti and Somalia every month, the Ethiopian News Agency
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Oumer Hussien, manager of the Eastern Branch
Customs Office in Dire Dawa, Ethiopia's second largest city, as
saying that coffee, fruits, cereals and khat are being exported
through the use of letter of credit to various countries.
</P>
<P>
The manager said some five million Dollars is currently being
secured monthly from the sale of khat, a stimulant exported to
neighboring Djibouti and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has diverted from Assab port of Eritrea to port of
Djibouti as its outlet since the outbreak of Ethio-Eritrean
border dispute on May 6, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The diversion has increased the business activities in eastern
part of Ethiopia which is bordered with Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
The Eastern Branch Customs Office will soon construct
additional ware-houses to promote import and export trade,
according to the manager. 
</P>
</TEXT>
