Jorge Mas Canosa, founder of the Cuban-American National
Foundation, sent him more than 200,000 U.S. dollars for his
operations against the Cuban leader.
</P>
<P>
Mas, who died last year, was embraced at the White House by
former presidents Ronald Reagan and George Bush and President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"A powerful force in both Florida and national elections, and a
prodigious campaign donor, Mr Mas played a decisive role in
persuading Mr. Clinton to change his mind and follow a course of
sanctions and isolation against Mr. Castro's Cuba," said the
paper. 
