<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gambia Seeks World Support to Improve Social Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Gambia will hold a two-day
round-table conference here in Geneva to seek support for the
country's improvements in population, education and health,
announced the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Gambian government, in collaboration with the UNDP, is
seeking 123.6 million U.S. dollars to address population density
problems, and to improve and provide greater access to health
services and education.
</P>
<P>
Gambia is a country of one million inhabitants, 60 percent of
whom live under the poverty line, according to UNDP statistics.
Its population growth rate of 4.2 percent makes it one of the
fastest growing population in the world with a density of 96
people per square kilometer.
</P>
<P>
The infant mortality rate in Gambia is as high as 85 children
per 1000 births and the maternal mortality rate is 10.5 per 1000
women.
</P>
<P>
