<HEADLINE> Russia Threatens to Withdraw Peacekeepers from Abkhazia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Russia Foreign Ministry Tuesday
warned that Russia may withdraw its peacekeeping forces from
Abkhazia, a breakaway Georgian region, if terrorist activity
continues against the peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, in a special statement
issued on Tuesday, the Russian Foreign Ministry condemned a
terrorist attack on Russian peacekeepers in the Gali district on
Monday night in which five servicemen were killed and another
three wounded.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that "the command of the Russian
peacekeeping troops was instructed to take measures for dealing
with terrorist groups on both sides of the security zone which is
subject to the mandate of the joint peacekeeping forces."
</P>
<P>
Russia is indignant at a joint statement by the Georgian
Interior and National Security Ministries "which does not contain
a word of regret over the killing of Russian servicemen but
contains a great deal of groundless accusations against the
peacekeeping forces and their command."
</P>
<P>
The two Georgian ministries in the joint statement accused the
Russian servicemen of looting and connivance with violence, the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign ministry also criticized Georgia for
ignoring its obligation to take effective measures to stop
terrorist and sabotage groups, armed units and armed persons from
penetrating into Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
Abkhazia seeking independence from Georgia has been in armed
conflicts with the Georgian government since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Both Georgia and Abkhazia are not meeting their commitments to
the peacekeepers, while the breakaway region has not yet created
conditions for the return of refugees to the Gali district, the
Russian ministry was quoted by Interfax as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
