<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Inflation Keeps Low Level in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Thanks to falling prices for
gasoline, lettuce, computers and cars, the U.S. inflation dipped
to nearly nothing in June, the Labor Department reported here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Price Index (CPI) increased a scant seasonally
adjusted 0.1 percent higher in June after rising a moderate 0.3
percent in the previous month, the most in a year and a half,
according to the department.
</P>
<P>
For the first half of the year, inflation ran at a 1.4 percent
annual rate, compared with an 11-year low of 1.7 percent for all
of last year. Much of that performance was attributable to energy
costs, which have fallen during five of the past six months.
</P>
<P>
They declined 0.7 percent in June and dropped at a 12.1 percent
annual rate during the first half of the year. Gasoline costs fell
0.9 percent in June and declined at a 21.1 percent rate for the
first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report, the Commerce Department reported that
consumer spending showed signs of slowing in June. Retail sales,
which make up about half of consumer spending and about a third of
overall economic activity, increased a lackluster 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
That followed a much more robust 1.2 percent increase in May,
the best in 10 months. In June, auto sales rose 0.1 percent but
department-store receipts fell 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the food and energy sectors, where prices swing
widely, prices crept up 0.1 percent. However, for the year so far,
inflation in these "core prices" were slightly worse than last
year. They're up at a 2.5 percent annual rate compared with a 2.2
percent rise for all of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Falling oil prices aren't the only factor helping taming the
inflation. Asia's currency devaluations have brought down import
prices and that has forced U.S. goods manufacturers to hold the
line on their prices.
</P>
<P>
New-car costs, for instance, fell 0.3 percent in June and were
down at a 1 percent annual rate for the first half of the year.
Computer prices fell 3.3 percent last month after drops of 4.5
percent in May and 2.4 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco costs, a hot spot for much of the year, fell 0.6
percent last month but were still up at a 12.1 percent annual rate
for the first half.
</P>
<P>
Medical care, which like many service industries is seeing more
inflation than goods-producing industries, rose 0.4 percent in
June and was up at a 3.7 percent rate for the first half.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, food prices rose just 0.1 percent in June after a
worrisome 0.6 percent surge in May. Lettuce prices dropped 28.1
percent and tomatoes were down 6.3 percent. Still, lettuce costs
were 28.5 percent higher than a year ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0072 </DOCNO>
