<HEADLINE> Non-State Economic Sectors Urged to Participate In Re-employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Wang Zhaoguo, vice-chairman of the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), today called on non-state economic sectors to
participate in the reemployment program to help unemployed workers
faced with difficult situations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a reemployment work conference held today in
Beijing, Wang said the non-State economy has witnessed
considerable progress and has emerged as a new economic growth
point since introduction of the reform and opening policies.
</P>
<P>
Statistics through the end of 1997 show that China has
registered more than 28 million self-employed individuals and
960,000 private enterprises which employ over 85 million people.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the government should encourage non-State enterprises
to increase their actual strength, while encouraging related
ventures to participate in the reform, transformation and
reorganization of State-owned enterprises by participating in
mergers, rentals, leases and outright purchases.
</P>
<P>
Jing Shuping, vice-chairman of the CPPCC National Committee and
president of the All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce,
said that participation in the reemployment effort also represents
an opportunity for the development of non-State enterprises.
</P>
<P>
