<HEADLINE> Chinese Observers Arrive in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Eight Chinese observers arrived
here Tuesday to join hundreds of others in helping secure free and
fair general elections in Cambodia on July 26.
</P>
<P>
Here at the invitation of the host nation, the Chinese were
received at the Pochentong Airport by officials of the Joint
International Observation Group and the Chinese Embassy.
</P>
<P>
The observation group was coordinated by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 short- and long-term international observers from
over 30 countries and non-governmental organizations will serve as
observers for the election.
</P>
<P>
They will be divided into about 235 two-person mobile
monitoring teams to visit polling stations on the election day.
</P>
<P>
The international observers can communicate with about 60,000
local colleagues, who are to be stationed in most polling places.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese observers are expected to be stationed in five
constituencies: Phnom Penh, Kandal, Kompong Cham, Komponng Chnang
and Kampot.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the Chinese Government sent 46 military and civilian
observers to this country.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming elections are organized by Cambodians
themselves and the estimated cost of 30 million U.S. dollars is
mostly donated by the international community.
</P>
<P>
The previous election in 1993 was run by the United Nations and
cost two billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
