<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungry Sudanese Stream into Government Garrison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- As hunger spreads in southern
Sudan, thousands of Sudanese are pouring into governmental
garrison towns to escape fighting and food shortage, the U.N.
World Food Program reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The fighting rages as small bands of unidentified armed men
are launching attacks and raiding local villages, causing
thousands of people to flee, said a WFP news release issued here.
</P>
<P>
The great influx is into Wau, the second largest
government-led town in the south. The town received an average
of 2,500 people per day in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
WFP has registered and is feeding 50,000 people who have
arrived since May. WFP now airlifts into Wau 300 tons of food
every week, doubling the number it has been bringing in since the
airlift began on May 30.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the women and children are horrendously
malnourished," Ismat Fahmi, WFP's deputy representative in
Khartoum, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Their weakened state is frighteningly similar to what we've
been seeing in some rebel-held areas of the south," said Fahmi.
</P>
<P>
Other government-held towns have also been receiving influxes
of people although on a smaller scale, according to the U.N. food
agency.
</P>
<P>
In Aweil, Bahr el Ghazal Province, at least 9,000 people need
humanitarian assistance. In Abyei and Meiram, west Kordofan area,
more than 15,000 are being fed by WFP.
</P>
<P>
"We're spending hours interviewing families to discover the
root causes for their sudden migration," said Fahmi. "More and
more, we are hearing that lack of food, disease and raids by
armed men are a big factor, forcing entire communities to flee
their villages."
</P>
<P>
Last week, WFP's Executive Director Catherine Bertini called
on the international community to make efforts in ending the
15-year war in southern Sudan between the Muslim-led government
and rebels fighting for more autonomy in animist and
Christian-populated southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The WFP is U.N.'s front-line agency in the fight against
global hunger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Build Joint Venture Cement Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Construction work on a
Bangladesh-France joint-venture cement plant in the private sector
will begin early next year, the national BSS news agency reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
All formalities have already been completed for buying lime
stone -- the raw material for producing cement -- from India, said
Michel Folliet, Managing Director of the French Lafarge-Surma
Company.
</P>
<P>
The 200-million-U.S.-dollar plant will be built in the
country's northeast district of Sylhet, the land development work
of which will begin in early September this year.
</P>
<P>
The plant, to be built with the most modern technology, would
initially produce 1.2 million tons of fine-quality cement
annually, Folliet said.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture cement plant, when completed, could save
Bangladesh 100 million dollars in foreign exchange for importing
cement from abroad, and create at least 2,000 jobs, he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, Bangladesh's cement consumption is between 3.5
million and 4 million tons a year, but the country's annual cement
production stands at about 1.2 million tons. Therefore, the
country has to spend a huge sum of foreign currency on importing
an average 2.4 million tons of cement every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
