<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warmer Ocean Water Devastates Marine Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The temperature of the ocean
along the U.S. West Coast, appears to have been warming steadily
since 1977, thus devastating marine life off California, according to
a report from The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Scripps Institution of Oceanography in La
Jolla, Calif., studied sea-surface temperatures along the West
Coast over the past 80 years and found large fluctuations in
temperature.
</P>
<P>
Since 1977, surface temperatures have increased by about 2
degrees Fahrenheit. The warmer water appears to have significant
effect on coastal ecosystems, leading to severe declines in
microscopic plankton, forests of kelp and the fish, birds and
mammals that feed on them.
</P>
<P>
But the scientists say it is unclear how much of the warmer
water is being caused by natural fluctuations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
