<HEADLINE> Jordan's King Visits U.S. for Medical Check </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Hussein left here
Tuesday to undergo medical check in the United States after
suffering fatigue resulted from a high fever.
</P>
<P>
After arriving in the U.S., the king, accompanied by his
U.S.-born Queen Noor, will receive medical check at the Mayo
Clinic, Rochester, Minnesota. The king used to have physical
examinations at this clinic twice a year.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's official news agency Petra quoted the king as saying
before his departure that he suffered from high temperatures at
an average of three times a day.
</P>
<P>
The king had undergone tests in Amman but nothing serious was
found, so he wanted to go to the U.S. for further examination,
said the news agency.
</P>
<P>
After visiting the U.S., King Hussein is expected in France
from July 21 to 23. He will meet President Jacques Chirac, Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin and other senior government officials there.
</P>
<P>
Their talks will deal with the latest developments of the
Mideast peace process as well as ways of pushing it forward,
especially on the Palestinian-Israeli track, Petra said.
</P>
<P>
The talks are also expected to cover bilateral relations and
ways of promoting them in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Hussein's last visit to France was in June last year. Chirac
paid an official visit to Jordan in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
Israel still sticks to a hard-line policy by expanding the
boundary of Jerusalem and rejecting a U.S. peace proposal which
calls for a 13.1 percent Israeli troops withdrawal from the West
Bank. The Palestinians have accepted the proposal. 
</P>
