<HEADLINE> EU Sends German Envoy to Reopen Talks with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will send a
German envoy to Minsk to try to resolve a dispute with the Belarus
government over diplomatic residences, the German Foreign Ministry
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under a decision made by EU foreign ministers in Brussels,
Germany's ambassador to Belarus, Horst Winkelmann, would return to
Minsk as the EU envoy to start the negotiations, the Foreign
Ministry added.
</P>
<P>
Winkelmann and ambassadors of Britain, France, Greece, Italy as
well as the United States were recalled from Minsk in June in
protest against a Belarus move to evict about 20 ambassadors from
their residences in Drozdy, a park-like compound they share with
President Alexander Lukashenko of Belarus.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats had been ordered by the Belarus authorities to
move out while repairs to the antiquated water and sewer system in
the residential compound took place.
</P>
<P>
Most of the envoys resisted, saying that their residences were
sovereign territory under the Vienna Convention.
</P>
<P>
Belarus reportedly had cut off water and electricity and barred
access to the houses.
</P>
<P>
The EU, however, saw a "positive signal" from a letter sent by
Lukashenko, in which he reportedly said that Minsk was ready to
discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
The letter was sent Saturday to Austria, which currently holds
the EU rotating presidency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
