<HEADLINE> Pakistan Has to Be Careful before Signing CTBT: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan said Tuesday Pakistan has to be very careful before
considering signing of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
Talking to the media in Lahore, Gohar said the positions of
Pakistan and India in regard to defense and balance of power are
differenct due to which Pakistan cannot link signing of CTBT with
India's attitude towards the Treaty or non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the CTBT is not a simple thing for which
tremendous pressure is being exerted on Pakistan, Gohar noted.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the CTBT, he said it includes Fissile Materials
Control Treaty (FMCT) which is something very serious as Pakistan
has far less Uranium than India and it has to see the strategic
and nuclear imbalance struck with the Indian test explosions.
</P>
<P>
"We have to correct the imbalance of power," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Minister said the Secretary General of the United
Nations, Kofi Annan, is coming to Pakistan before the Summit of
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation scheduled to be
held in Colombo at the end of this month for re-structuring the
talks between Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
Similarly wide ranging meetings will also be held with U.S.
Deputy Secretary of State for South Asian Affairs Strobe Talbott
when he visits pakistan on July 23 and 24 to evolve strategy for
hitting the core issue (Kashmir) between Pakistan and India to get
some concrete solution.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question, he said Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif had
four meetings with former Indian Premier Inder K. Gujral, which
like other 50 bilateral talks, were fruitless.
</P>
<P>
In view of this experience, Pakistan now wants some meaningful
dialogues with its neighbor of India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
