<HEADLINE> Canada's Credit Unions Eye Banding Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The credit union industry in Canada
is examining a proposal that could turn the grass-roots movement
into banks, a report said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A new national task force has been formed to examine whether
the credit unions can better combine the delivery of their
services under one umbrella.
</P>
<P>
Bobby McVeigh, head of the task force, said he expects a system
with standardized service and products across the country, "so it
doesn't matter where I am doing business."
</P>
<P>
However, McVeigh said, the planned restructuring would continue
to emphasize community roots.
</P>
<P>
The task force was expected to table a report by the end of
this summer. It would then be put to a vote.
</P>
<P>
More than 4.2 million Canadians belong to credit unions.
Across the country, there are 873 credit unions with total assets
worth 32 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The industry has been under pressure to develop a strategy to
get a better position themselves in the fast-changing
financial-service sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
