<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Stresses Democratic Legislation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li joined in discussions and solicited the opinions of
government officials from various departments in Changchun
concerning the law on land management.
</P>
<P>
Officials stressed the need for tight controls on land
distribution right, and contended that related rights should
remain in the hands of either the central or provincial
governments. Others proposed that law should include articles on
the development and regulation of the real estate market.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China's over 900 million rural people depend on
land. Nonetheless, substantial tracts of arable land have been
lost to new construction projects and waste in recent years. The
new land management law must ensure sustainable growth for our
country's future, said Li.
</P>
<P>
Presidents and Party secretaries from 13 Jilin universities and
colleges expressed their opinions concerning the nation's first
higher education law which is currently under consideration by the
legislature.
</P>
<P>
Li agreed that the university presidents should be granted
greater authority over the management and development of
respective universities.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the existing educational system should be
reformed to produce versatile graduates needed for the constantly
changing society and market.
</P>
<P>
Li also explored the difficulties state-owned enterprises face
in the former heavy industrial base, in addition to holding
discussions with government and enterprise officials concerning
redundant workers and the social security system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
