<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Capable to Come Out Of Economic Crisis: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Tuesday that Pakistan is fully capable of wriggling
out of the current economic crisis as it has inherent potential to
face challenges.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani people will come out of the crisis very well,
Sharif said at a meeting attended by economic experts and
businessmen at the Prime Minister House, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
"All attempts to exploit post-May 28 developments by the vested
interests would fail and the nation would soon tide over its
difficulties," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
He said the present economic crisis is a temporary one and
would be over soon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sharif noted that "nothing is more precious than the
preservation of our political independence and territorial
integrity."
</P>
<P>
"If any arm-twisting tactic is applied to Pakistan, the country
would resist it with full force and might," Sharif said, adding:
"We will never submit to any amount of coercion or pressure."
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan's detonation of nuclear tests on May 28 was
necessary to ensure the continued existence of the country as an
independent and sovereign nation.
</P>
<P>
He also made it clear that Pakistan is a peace-loving country
and it has no aggressive designs against any country.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly believe in economic and social development of the
region," he added.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the country's economic situation was
reviewed and a number of suggestions to improve it were
considered.
</P>
<P>
Sharif asked the participants to make specific recommendations
for the uplift of the economy and for enhancing the country's
foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the participants to suggest ways and means for
protecting the poor and needy from the negative trend of price
hikes and providing them with special safety nets.
</P>
<P>
Economic experts at the meeting will continue deliberations for
three days to finalize their recommendations to overcome the
economic problems facing the country.
</P>
<P>
These recommendations will be presented to the prime minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
