<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Inflation Set to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's year-on-year inflation
continues to rise and was pegged at 29.8 percent for the month of
June.
</P>
<P>
This represents a 0.5 percentage point increase from the level
of 29.3 percent in May, according to the latest review released
here Tuesday by central statistical office on price trends.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency quoted analysts as saying that the
increase was mainly due to an upsurge in the consumer prices of
food items and medical care.
</P>
<P>
They expected inflation to be above 30 percent by the year
end, which means the inflation target of 19 percent set by the
International Monetary Fund would not be achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales In UK Show First Fall In Three Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Britain's retailers suffered their
worst sales performance for more than three years in June as
interest rate rises, cold and wet weather and the World Cup kept
consumers away from the high street.
</P>
<P>
The British Retail Consortium's latest sales monitor, published
Tuesday, shows a 0.1 percent fall in sales last month compared
with a year earlier -- the first decline since March 1995.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Higginson, Chairman of the Consortium's Economic Affairs
Committee, said: "The appalling weather affected sales badly in
some sectors, and the World Cup kept viewers at home on match
days."
</P>
<P>
"This move into negative territory confirms the slowdown in
sales that we have seen for some time," he added.
</P>
<P>
Retailers in the clothing, footwear and furniture sectors were
hardest hit with the wet weather heavily affecting sales of summer
stock.
</P>
<P>
The consortium also said the series of interest rate increases
since the same period last year continued to hurt consumer
confidence and high-street spending.
</P>
<P>
The strong pound and Tube strikes were among the main causes
for the retail sales slump last month, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
