<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Palestinians Welcome U.N. Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Tuesday welcomed the U.N. Security Council
statement that urges Israel not to expand Jerusalem, while Israel
expressed "regret" over it.
</P>
<P>
PNA Cabinet Secretary Ahmad Abdel Rahman told the Voice of
Palestine radio that the Security Council Presidential statement
is a moral and political condemnation to the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet adopted on June 21 a plan for Jerusalem
expansion, which puts some Jewish settlements in the West Bank
under the jurisdiction of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, who see Jerusalem as the capital of their
future state, sharply criticized the plan, saying it was a
declaration of war against the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Tuesday, the Israeli Foreign Ministry
said "we regret" the U.N. statement passed Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Israel has already clarified that the Cabinet decision of June
21, 1998 does not contradict the agreements between Israel and the
Palestinians," the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The status of Jerusalem is one of the most sensitive and
contentious issues in Israeli-Palestinian negotiations. The
agreements signed between the two sides forbid any unilateral
actions to change its status until the final status talks are held.
</P>
<P>
The ministry reiterated that the plan "is municipal in nature"
and is intended to extend Jerusalem's municipal jurisdiction only
to areas west of the city. The Security Council statement "ignores
these facts," it added.
</P>
<P>
"Israel will continue to work for the development and
prosperity of Jerusalem, for the benefit of all its inhabitants,"
the ministry's statement said.
</P>
<P>
Rahman expressed the hope that the Security Council's position
will oblige Israel to halt settlements and expansion policy which
violates the signed agreements and endanger the entire peace
process.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the U.N. statement and its condemnation lacks
the mechanism of forcing Israel to drop its Jerusalem expansion
scheme.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Security Council, which began debate on the
Jerusalem expansion plan early this month, fell short of adopting
a resolution condemning Israel's act as pressed for by many
countries, particularly the Arabs. The United States and Britain
have led a diplomatic drive to prevent the Security Council from
voting on such a resolution.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council Presidential statement said Israel's
Jerusalem expansion plan would pose damage to the Mideast peace
process and asked Israel to stop implementing this plan.
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace process has been stalled for 16 months since
Israel started to build a settlement in the traditionally Arab
East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani FM Optimistic About IMF Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan Tuesday expressed his optimism about a positive decision
by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on the release of aid to
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Lahore Chamber of Commerce and Industry, Gohar
said the IMF has postponed its decision for another 24 hours on
whether it should continue its financial support to Pakistan or
punish it for going nuclear.
</P>
<P>
IMF has delayed the release of promised financial assistance to
Pakistan under the pressure of G-8 (Group of Eight) countries
because of Pakistan's detonation of nuclear devices at the end of
May.
</P>
<P>
Gohar hoped that the outcome of the IMF Board meeting would be
positive.
</P>
<P>
He said Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has sent missions to
friendly countries to seek their help at such a crucial juncture,
and hoped these efforts would bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
Gohar noted that the people of Pakistan had suffered far worse
conditions at the time of Pakistan's establishment and has the
potential to pass through the prevailing difficult situation
without any complications.
</P>
<P>
The situation is not as bleak as it is being painted by certain
quarters, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that the impact of economic sanctions has
not filtered through yet as it would take four to five months for
the sanctions to hurt the national economy.
</P>
<P>
"We were aware of the sanctions and opted for explosions only
after considering the sanctions and embargoes which will remain
effective for a year," Gohar said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
