<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada to Consult Congress on Marcos Wealth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- President Joseph Estrada said
Tuesday that he would consult Congress on a proposed out-of-court
settlement between the government and the Marcoses of the wealth
of late president Ferdinand Marcos.
</P>
<P>
"We will have to ask our congressional leaders about this. I
will seek their advice," he said, confident that with all the
heads of the three branches of government being put together, his
government will not make a mistake in making a deal with the
Marcoses.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Estrada said that if the out-of-court settlement would
"benefit our people, why not...as long as it will be for the
interest of the greater majority of our people and it is legal,
nobody can stop me."
</P>
<P>
According to a deal drafted in 1993, the government and the
Marcoses would divide Marcos' wealth on a 75-25 base in favor of
the government while the share of the Marcoses is tax-free.
</P>
<P>
However, Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said that nothing
definite has yet been reached on the issue between the present
administration and the Marcoses.
</P>
<P>
"It's hard to agree unless we see it on paper," Zamora said, in
response to questions as to whether the tax-free share of the
Marcoses in the 75-25 deal is acceptable to the government.
</P>
<P>
Marcos, who was ousted in 1986 and died three years later in
Hawaii, the United States, has been accused of amassing at least 5
billion dollars of wealth during his 20-year rule of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
