<HEADLINE> Prolonged Heat Wave Hits Shanghai, Wuhan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, one of China's major
metropolitan area, has reeled from a prolonged heat wave in recent
weeks, with today's temperature climbing to 38.6 degrees
Centigrade, the city's highest recorded temperature in 54 years.
</P>
<P>
The heat wave hit the city on June 30, with the highest daily
temperatures remaining above 34 degrees Centigrade. Local
meteorologists predict the heat wave will continue till through
late July.
</P>
<P>
Wuhan, the capital city of central China's Hubei Province, has
also experienced a heat wave which has driven the mercury to 39
degree Centigrade since July 12.
</P>
<P>
Local hospitals have reported numerous cases of people
suffering from heatstrokes and related intestinal diseases, as
well as fever and colds. Sources from the Tongji Hospital and
several other large hospitals in the city report the number of
people seeking medical attention for heatstrokes over the three
days equals the total number for the summers of both 1996 and
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
