<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Manufacturers Urged to Penetrate Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of Zambia
Chambers of Commerce and Industry (ZCCI) has urged Zambian
manufacturers to start immediately working on how best to
penetrate the southern African market.
</P>
<P>
In an interview Monday in Lusaka, Gideon Phiri, chief
executive of ZCCI called on local manufacturers to take advantage
of the trade agreement Zambia signed Monday with Southern African
Customs Union (SACU) member countries, The Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It is time for local manufacturers to start penetrating the
South African market which offers an estimated 100 million U.S.
Dollars for the first year of trade, said Phiri.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Zambia's manufacturing sector stands to gain
massively from the trade agreement because South Africa will not
demand reciprocal levels of trade after the agreement becomes
effective.
</P>
<P>
Phiri attached importance to the quality of goods and advising
the producers to produce goods according to market needs.
</P>
<P>
"We should not belittle the quality of the products we are
producing because quality is dependent of the market," said
Phiri, adding "a manufacturer will produce goods according to
what this market requires."
</P>
<P>
Under the trade agreement signed in Pretoria, South Africa,
Zambia will have a reciprocal trade arrangement with other SACU
member countries including Lesotho, Swaziland, Botswana, Namibia
and South Africa while a non-reciprocal scheme to allow Zambian
foods to enter duty free will apply toward South Africa.
</P>
<P>
On his departure Sunday for South Africa to sign the
agreement, Enock Kavindele, Minister of Commerce, Trade and
Industry said the trade pact will help boost Zambia's exports to
the southern African region.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has complained in the past years that its trade
partners in the region have been trying to make Zambia a dumping
ground for their goods by providing subsidies to their companies
since the country liberalized its economy in early 1990s and the
play ground is not level.
</P>
<P>
Zambian products have been finding it difficult to enter these
markets while products from the same countries have been flooding
the local market at cheap prices compared with the same Zambian
products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
