<HEADLINE> HK to Retain Competitiveness in Garment Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is still able to
retain a competitive edge in the garment industry, said Chan Wing
Kee, council member of the Hong Kong Trade Development Council,
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is because local manufacturers have set up low cost
offshore bases around the world, especially in the Chinese
mainland.
</P>
<P>
Even with currency devaluation elsewhere in the region, the
production cost in the Chinese mainland is still competitive
compared with other Asian countries, Chan said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the Fashion Week for
Spring/Summer '99 from July 14 to 17, Chan noted that Hong Kong
remains the preferred sourcing center in the Asia-Pacific region
for international fashion as Hong Kong manufacturers and traders
are reputed to be stable, reliable, and efficient in managing
product development, production and quality control.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said Hong Kong has also evolved into a service
center in which design and marketing are the key areas of
expertise, with many local designers making a name for themselves
in the domestic and international markets.
</P>
<P>
In face of the changing market demand and increasing
competition from other countries, especially from Asian countries,
he said that quick response has become increasingly important for
Hong Kong garment industry.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Asian currency crisis should not have a marked
impact on Hong Kong garment exports in the short term but will
most likely lead to intensified price competition in the medium
term.
</P>
<P>
In response, Hong Kong garment manufacturers should continue to
sharpen their competitiveness in terms of price and quality, while
shortening delivery time by using sophisticated production methods
and modern communications technologies to supply the right
products in precise quantities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Garment industry is still Hong Kong's leading exporter,
with total exports of clothing and clothing accessories exceeding
178.8 billion HK dollars (22.92 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997, he
said, adding that the Fashion Week reinforces the importance of
its garment industry.
</P>
<P>
At this Spring/Summer event, 314 exhibitors from 13 countries
and regions are displaying a wide array of high quality fashion
products, ranging from fashion garments to accessories and
trade-related services.
</P>
<P>
The fashion design talents of the region will demonstrate their
design artistry and creative craftsmanship in a series of fashion
shows, further enhancing Hong Kong's leading status as the
region's fashion center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
