<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Comments On Peace For Palestinian People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat, wearing his trademark headdress and military uniform and
punctuating his remarks with strong gestures, told Chinese
journalists in a meeting today that his life-long pursuit has been
to let the Palestinian people live freely in a free-land.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the Palestinian cause is reaching an end, he said
here at the beginning of a three-day official visit at the
invitation of President Jiang Zemin, even thought the peace talks
have been stalemated.
</P>
<P>
He said that there should be more pressure from the
international community to force the Israeli government to change
its position and implement the agreements already reached between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"Peace is not only for Palestine and Israel, but for the entire
Middle East region," Arafat said, "If peace is not protected, we
will fight hard to save peace."
</P>
<P>
Israel should make an effort to break the current deadlock in
the Mideast peace talks so that the Mideast issue can be resolved
in a comprehensive, just and thorough way, he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who is on his eleventh China visit, said that China is
part of an international balance in the peace process and can play
a bigger role in the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He said he had frank and detailed discussions with President
Jiang on the Mideast peace process and the Palestinian cause and
that the Palestinians will never forget China's continuous support.
</P>
<P>
Arafat devoted himself to the Palestine liberation cause when
he was still a young man. Now approaching his 70s, he witnessed
the vicissitudes of the Palestinian cause in the past decades.
</P>
<P>
Some 24 years ago, Arafat first addressed the UN General
Assembly at the beginning of the Palestine Liberation
Organization. The PLO, then under his chairmanship, was granted
observer status in the UN.
</P>
<P>
The 52nd UN General Assembly last Tuesday approved a resolution
to upgrade the status of Palestine to near statehood from that of
observer and Arafat called this support from the international
community for the cause of peace.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Arafat was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize together with
his long-time foes, the late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin
and former Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres. After that time
he gave up his pistol at public occasions, even though it had been
a part of him for decades.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process will no doubt move forward, he
said, because it is the common aspiration of the Palestinians, the
Israelis, the Arabs, and the whole international community.
</P>
<P>
He said that Palestinians have the right to declare an
independent Palestinian state in May 1999 in accordance with
relevant international agreements, and the schedule remains
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
"I'm in good health and confident to see the advent of peace in
the Middle East region," he concluded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
