<HEADLINE> EU Assists Charity Projects for Gypsie Minorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- European Commissioner for
External Affairs Hans van den Broek showed on Tuesday European
Commission's assistance to gypsies in eastern Europe by starting a
truck carrying charity materials bound for Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
The truck contained a brick-making machine that was donated to
a social housing project in Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
The donation was made by European college graduates who have
worked as interns in the European Commission. Twice a year some
600 graduates participate in this traineeship program.
</P>
<P>
There is now an estimated total of 8 million Roma/gypsies in
Europe after they started leaving northeastern India in the 11th
century.
</P>
<P>
A vast majority of the gypsies, 6 million, now live in central
and eastern Europe, ranging from between 1.8 million and 2.5
million in Romania to between 8,000 and 10,000 in Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials said that as a minority, Roma/gypsies
communities tend to suffer from social and cultural exclusion in
most European countries and their nomadic way of life have
rendered the defense of their rights difficult. 
</P>
</TEXT>
