<HEADLINE> Singapore Stock Market Ends Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to slide
Tuesday on Singapore Stock Market as sentiment remained weary amid
the recessionary gloom in the region.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) lost 10.70
points to close at 1,042.44 points.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume dropped to 89.78 million shares valued at
139.69 million Singapore dollars (82.17 million U.S. dollars).
Gainers led losers by 135 to 121 while 337 stocks remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
DBS Land, a major developer, remained the most active stock as
it registered a turnover of 5.85 million units. It was followed by
MBF Cap which had 4.85 million shares done. UOB F was next with
2.72 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
ChemInde was the top gainer of the day as it gained 30 cents to
end at 2.10 Singapore dollars. OCBC F edged up 15 cents to finish
at 5.75 Singapore dollars. Parkway inched up by 14 cents to close
at 2.74 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 was the biggest loser as it lost
80 cents to finish at 21.60 Singapore dollars. JacksInt fell by 40
cents to end at 0.80 Singapore dollars. Teh Res was down 38 cents
to close at 0.90 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said share prices, which lifted for a while in
Tuesday's early trading by firmer regional currencies, closed
marginally softer with trading thinned by the absence of fresh
factors.
</P>
<P>
Activity was from investors and broking houses trading their
property accounts on an intraday basis.
</P>
<P>
Dealers also said fears of more corporate failures in the
region, uncertainty toward Japan's economic reforms and the threat
of a slowdown in the region's economies put a lid on gains.
</P>
<P>
They also said the market was awaiting more news from Japan,
and needed to hear news about Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto's successor and where the country's economic reform were
headed for clearer near-term direction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
