<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kim Jong-pil Allowed to Continue Acting as Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Constitutional Court of South
Korea Tuesday dismissed as improper the demand by the major
opposition Grand National Party (GNP) to declare unconstitutional
the appointment of Kim Jong-pil as acting prime minister by
President Kim Dae-jung without parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
The court ruled that the GNP lawmakers have no right to bring
the case to the court, saying that the parliament is authorized to
bring the case to the court through a resolution.
</P>
<P>
"That's because the appointment of the prime minister is the
sole right of the National Assembly (parliament), not the right of
individual lawmakers," said the court.
</P>
<P>
In March, President Kim appointed Kim Jong-pil as acting prime
minister after the GNP, which holds the majority of seats in the
parliament, failed to vote over his formal appointment as prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
However, the GNP claimed it illegal that President Kim made Kim
Jong-pil as acting prime minister and asked the Constitutional
Court to made a judgement and issue an injunction against the
appointment.
</P>
<P>
The GNP has been opposing Kim Jong-pil, who formed an alliance
with Kim Dae-jung for winning the 15th presidential election last
December, as prime minister, arguing that Kim Jong-pil is not
qualified for the second highest post in the government which will
lead the nation to overcome the current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The 72-year-old Kim Jong-pil, who is on his tour to Europe, has
been a heavyweight boxer in South Korea's political arena for
nearly 40 years and once took the post of prime minister of the
country. He was also the founder of the nation's Central
Intelligence Agency after helping late President Park Chung-hee
mastermind the 1961 coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
