<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Shilling Gains Sharply Against US Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Somali Shalling appreciated
sharply Tuesday morning, with 7,500 Shillings to one U.S. Dollar,
compared to 8,400 Shillings to one U.S. Dollar Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The capital city of Mogadishu is floating with U.S. Dollars as
the Somali Shilling has made a dramatic increase in value against
the dollars.
</P>
<P>
Each one U.S. Dollar has lost more than 900 Shillings in just
less than 48 hours, the fastest appreciation the Shilling has
ever made against any of the hard currencies commonly used in
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts could not find a scientific reason to the
sharp increase in the value of the Shilling.
</P>
<P>
However, they characterized the immediate change as a
superficial overflow of the U.S. Dollars injected into the
economy.
</P>
<P>
The economists had supported their view with the stability of
the prices on all commodities including food and cosmetics which
should have collapsed in price with the dollars in the normal
economic recoveries.
</P>
<P>
According to the traders in Mogadishu's main Bakara market,
the exchange center has been washed with a lot of U.S. Dollars
since the faction leaders returned to the capital from their trip
to Libya Saturday.
</P>
<P>
An unconfirmed report and rumors said that the relatives of
the faction leaders are those who are especially pouring the
dollars in the market since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Another factor obviously affecting the market is a press
release issued Sunday by the faction leaders, stating that Libya
has already donated 250,000 U.S. Dollars for the establishment of
an administration in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The faction leaders also signed a draft agreement at a
luncheon sponsored by Libya's Ambassador to Somalia Al-Sayid
Ma'tuq for the faction leaders Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The four supreme leaders were made for the high council of
Mogadishu's administration, two co-chairmen (Ali Mahdi and
Hussein Aidid) and two deputy co-chairmen (Mohamed Qanyare and
Osman Atto).
</P>
<P>
They have also signed that Mogadishu's main installations, the
air and sea ports, will be opened on 18th this month, a pledge
hardly possible.
</P>
<P>
The optimistic mood thus resulted from their trip to Libya for
a possible political settlement for Mogadishu is also widely
voiced in the streets of the capital, another factor encouraging
the Somali Shilling to jump on its feet.
</P>
<P>
However, the pessimists assert that as usual, the faction
leaders will simply take the money and instead of using it for
the common good, they may turn it for the use against their
rivals within their factions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
