<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Govt. Offers Amnesty to Surrendered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Sierra Leonean government has
offered amnesty to rebel soldiers committing atrocities in the
country and enjoined to surrender in the name of national
reconciliation, according to a report reaching here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Septumus Kaikai, spokesman for President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah,
was quoted as saying that rebels had been granted amnesty were
mostly the child soldiers conscripted into the army.
</P>
<P>
Kaikai said that this group of rebels whose ages fall between
nine and 10 did not join the army voluntarily. However, he added
that they had spent about six years in the civil war.
</P>
<P>
He accused the leaders of the rebels still loyal to the
Revolutionary United Front and the Armed Forces Revolutionary
Council of deliberately holding on to the youths who, he said,
were "given drugs which destabilize them."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman assured that this group of rebels still
committing atrocities in the eastern part of the country would be
granted amnesty if they surrendered to the Kabbah government.
</P>
<P>
But he ruled out a blanket amnesty for all rebels in the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The government was still "looking for the leaders of the
mayhem and the atrocity," Kaikai said.
</P>
<P>
Since the military government were chased out of the capital
Freetown in mid-February, rebels have been concentrated in the
eastern part of Kailan district, killing and maiming innocent
citizens for supporting the government of Kabbah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
