<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passenger Services Continue to Improve at HK's New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Within one week of opening, the
efficiency of passenger services at the new Hong Kong
International Airport have equaled, and in many respects
surpassed, those at Kai Tak, according to Hong Kong's Airport
Authority (AA).
</P>
<P>
More than 600,000 passengers have passed through the new
airport since the opening day on July 6 and the timeliness of
arriving and departing flights has improved steadily during the
week, the AA said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The number of those arriving early or on time has risen from 32
percent on July 7 to 58 percent by noon Monday.
</P>
<P>
By Monday 54 percent of flights had left on schedule, 96
percent within 30 minutes and all flights had left within an hour.
On July 7, only 15 percent of flights left within 30 minutes of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
The average delay for departures has gone from more than one
hour and 40 minutes on July 7 to just 12 minutes by Monday,
despite Monday morning's heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
There has also been a strong improvement in baggage handling,
with passengers now waiting from five to 20 minutes on average for
their bags after completing immigration formalities.
</P>
<P>
Airport Authority Corporate Development Director Clinton Leeks
said the figures showed that passenger services were now normal at
the new airport.
</P>
<P>
"While there continues to be room for improvement, we are
generally pleased that the passenger terminal is achieving the
levels of efficiency it was designed for and this view appears to
be supported by comments we are receiving from many passengers
themselves," Leeks said.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Federal Express Corporation (FedEx), the
world's largest air express transportation company, announced that
it has started operating five new weekly flights between Hong Kong
and the FedEx Asia Pacific Hub in Subic Bay, the Philippines, in
order to meet the increased demand for express services at its new
facilities at the Hong Kong International Airport.
</P>
<P>
"The successful start-up of our express facilities at the Asia
Airfreight Terminal since the opening day has substantially
enhanced our efficiency, enabling us to deliver faster and more
reliable service for customers in Hong Kong, and for shipments
from around the region and the world," said Michael Ducker,
president of FedEx Asia Pacific Division. 
</P>
</TEXT>
