<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Retail Sales Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's retail sales volume
rose 9.6 percent on a year-on-year basis to 71.3 billion yuan
during the first half of this year, the city's statistics bureau
reports.
</P>
<P>
This was 2.6 percentage points higher than the national
average, and because the prices had a declining rate for the past
six years, the actual growth is more than 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
Video cameras, motorcycles and computers sold well, while
clothing sales dropped. Supermarket sales accounted for 41 percent
of the total while department stores accounted for only about 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that Shanghai's business is becoming very
competitive, but most companies' marketing strategy is restricted
to cutting prices and offering discounts.
</P>
<P>
Many companies are struggling along with next to zero
profits. Profits were down by 0.06 percentage points to 1.22
percent during the six-month period.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai expects to see retail sales increase by 11 percent to
147 billion yuan for the whole year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Crimes Rise by 4.2 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's criminal cases
increased by 4.2 percent in 1997 over that of 1996, Tanzanian
Minister of Home Affairs Ali Ameir Mohammed has said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 528,710 criminal cases were reported in the
country, compared to 507,507 in 1996, the minister told
parliament in the central city of Dodoma Monday.
</P>
<P>
Of the cases, 512,832 were reported in the mainland while the
rest in the Zanzibar isles, Tuesday's Daily News quoted the
minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed, who is also a member of parliament for Donge, said
that in 1997 there were 2,355 murder cases in which 2,403 people
lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
The figure went down by 28 cases when compared to 2,383 murder
cases reported in 1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also told the legislators that there were 885
incidents of armed robbery during 1997 with loss of property
worth 2.9 billion Shillings (about 4.3 million U.S. Dollars on
current basis).
</P>
<P>
However, he said, goods worth 485.9 million Shillings were
recovered and some 1,556 armed bandits were seized by the police.
</P>
<P>
The minister conceded that there is an increase of 21 percent
in armed robbery incidents.
</P>
<P>
He said a total of 82,539.5 kilograms of bhang were impounded
by the police in 3,747 incidents in 1997 as compared with 4,711
kilograms seized in 3,486 incidents in 1996. In addition, some
five kilograms of narcotic drugs were seized last year.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed said that the war on such drugs is an uphill task and
urged parliamentarians to lend their support.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Anti-drug Unit under the supervision of
Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye will be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Last year, some 269 arms and 1,256 rounds of ammunition were
netted, a 45.5 percent increase compared to 1995. Some 485
suspects were arrested for illegal possession of such arms, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
During the 1998/99 fiscal year, the Tanzanian government will
strive to strengthen patrols to control pirate activities,
Mohammed further said.
</P>
<P>
The police force will also train auxiliary police in public
and private institutions to tighten security in office buildings,
he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
