<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Willing to Discuss Regional Nuclear Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan High Commissioner to
India Ashraf Jehangir Qazi said Tuesday that his country was
willing to discuss with India at the Colombo summit of the South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) on July 29-31 a
regional nuclear test ban pact formalizing the moratoria declared
by the two countries on further nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
In an interview to Press Trust of India (PTI) here, Qazi said
that Islamabad was keen to enter into a new hopeful and
constructive phase of relations with New Delhi when Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif meets Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee on the fringes of the three-day Colombo summit.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in 1985, embraces Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the two prime ministers would be of inherent
importance as this would be Sharif's first interaction with the
BJP-led coalition government in the aftermath of the nuclear
explosions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The relations between India and Pakistan have become more tense
following the nuclear tests by the two countries in May. The world
community has time and again urged the two countries to take
measures to ease tension through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"We have already indicated (to New Delhi) that peace and
security including confidence building measures as well as the
root cause of our tension, Jammu and Kashmir, are of primary and
urgent concern that should be addressed by the two sides," Qazi
said.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the question of signing the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty (CTBT), he said that Pakistan would keep all options open
including considering joining the treaty without India being a
party to it, indicating a clear shift in Pakistan's earlier stand.
</P>
<P>
Previously Pakistan maintained that it would sign the treaty
only after India signs it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
