<HEADLINE> Nigeria Names New Chief of Naval Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Former Minister of Health Jubirla
Ayinla has been named Nigeria's new Chief of Naval Staff to
replace Okhai Mike Akhigbe, who was sworn last week as Chief of
General Staff.
</P>
<P>
Ayinla's appointment, which took immediate effect, was
announced in a statement Monday by David Attah, Chief Press
Secretary to Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
Ayinla was the Federal Minister of Health in the Federal
Executive Council (cabinet) which was dissolved last week. He
was Minister of Commerce and Tourism from July 1996 to November
1997.
</P>
<P>
Ayinla's predecessor Akhigbe was sworn as Chief of General
Staff last week by Abubakar to fill the vacuum created by the
fall of Oladipo Diya, who was arrested last December for
involvement in an alleged coup plot.
</P>
<P>
Also sworn in at the same time was Alami Dagash as the new
Chief of Defense Staff, a position held by Abubakar until he
succeeded late military leader General Sani Abacha on June 9.
</P>
<P>
In what looks like a major reshuffle of the armed forces, the
Army Command Monday announced the redeployment of some senior
commanders.
</P>
<P>
Victor Malu, former commander of the West African sub-regional
peacekeeping force in Liberia known as ECOMOG, was appointed the
commander of the Lagos Garrison, perhaps to strengthen the
security in the stronghold of Nigeria's opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
Before his new appointment, Malu was the general officer
commanding the Second Mechanized Division in the southwestern
City of Ibadan, a position once held by late General Abacha and
now taken over by Major-General Felix Mujakperuo.
</P>
<P>
Bashir Magashi was named the new commander of the Nigerian
Defense Academy, filling the vacuum left by Alami Dagash.
</P>
<P>
Leo Ajiborisha was appointed principal staff officer to the
new leader Abubakar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
