<HEADLINE> Tanzania Tries to Curb Dynamite Fishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
planned to buy a marine patrol boat to add muscles to the
fight against rampant dynamite fishing.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Natural Resources and Tourism Zakia Meghji
revealed this at a parliamentary session on Monday in central
city of Dodoma.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the Daily News on Tuesday, Meghji
said that the Fisheries Department of the ministry has set aside
funds for purchasing the vessel, but she did not disclose its
cost.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, however, is unable to buy a vehicle for every
district for lack of funds, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Meghji appealed to the licensed miners not to
transfer explosives to the hands of illegal fishermen.
</P>
<P>
Although dynamite fishing is prohibited in the Indian Ocean
and all lakes of the country, criminal cases related to the
problem have been frequently reported.
</P>
<P>
Meghji said that the government will take measures to net and
prosecute all of the illegal fishermen.
</P>
<P>
During a crackdown on dynamite fishing between July and
November in 1997, the police and Tanzania People's Defense Forces
(TPDF) arrested 102 suspects and impounded seven tons of fish in
Dar es Salaam, Coast and Tanga regions along the Indian Ocean.
However, the crackdown campaign was weakened by the shortage of
modern facilities.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Tanzanian Vice-President Omar Ali Juma stressed the
need to review the existing laws and regulations
governing dynamite fishing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
