<HEADLINE> Ugandan Vice-President Gets FAO Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Vice-President Specioza
Wandira Kazibwe has been awarded the Ceres Medal by the Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) for her longstanding work for food
security and agricultural development in the country.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued Tuesday by the president's office said
that Director-General of FAO Jacques Diouf presented the award to
Kazibwe at the State House Nakasero Monday.
</P>
<P>
The citation for the award said that the vice-president had
for many years striven to combat hunger and rural poverty by
promoting and supporting the emancipation and empowerment of
rural women and their effective integration in the development
process.
</P>
<P>
Kazibwe's work for agricultural modernization and food
security within a context of social justice has contributed to
highlighting the crucial role of women in feeding the world,
the press release said.
</P>
<P>
After accepting the award, Kazibwe said that the award is a
recognition of the role played by women in Uganda as well as in
Africa in food production.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, President Yoweri Museveni was presented
a complementary award for his support to the vice-president in
her work in this field.
</P>
<P>
Diouf paid tribute to Museveni for his vision and wisdom in
understanding clearly that agriculture is the soul of the nation
and that women occupy a central place in production. 
</P>
