<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK, Macao, Guangdong Explore Ways to Develop Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong, Macao and Guangdong
are jointly exploring ways to further develop tourism on the
basis of their different social systems, natural resources unique
to each destination.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center here Tuesday, Amy Chan, executive director of
the Hong Kong Tourist Association, Lu Weixiong, director of the
Guangdong Provincial Tourism Bureau, and Suzete Saraiva, deputy
director of the Macao Government Tourist Office, outlined their
future objectives for joint cooperation in tourism.
</P>
<P>
Chan said that the tourism authorities and governments of
Guangdong, Hong Kong and Macao all value this close relationship.
The Hong Kong-Guangdong Cooperation Joint Conference, proposed by
Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
Tung Chee Hwa, was set up in March this year to promote their
communications and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Starting from 1990, tourist communities of Hong Kong, Macao and
Guangdong held discussions on many occasions, exploring
possibilities of cooperation. In June 1993, representatives of the
three parties agreed to set up a working group to jointly promote
tourism.
</P>
<P>
In December that year, the Pearl River Delta Tourism Marketing
Organization was formally established with a view to attracting
more overseas visitors.
</P>
<P>
In the long term, she said, this is a significant task as the
results of study will not only enhance the attractiveness of this
region for overseas tourists, but also provide a basis for a
balanced approach to improving tourism infrastructure and
developing new scenic spots and tourism products in the region.
</P>
<P>
Lu said: "To further promote tourism in all three areas, we
will endeavor to implement measures that will make travel even
more convenient."
</P>
<P>
"We will also assess how to best enhance the flow of
information between the three destinations, and increase
cooperation in human resources training to heighten the tourism
competitiveness," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, the Organization announced the
completion of the "Pearl River Delta Hotel Inventory 1997" which
comprises a comprehensive listing of hotels in Guangdong, Hong
Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
Saraiva noted that this is the first of the inventory projects
jointly conducted by the three members of the Organization.
</P>
<P>
Another project currently underway is the Product Inventory
which will provide information on the three areas, covering
tourist attractions, shopping, dining and entertainment, sports
facilities and venues as well as convention and exhibition venues,
performance venues and inter-city transportation, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Organization has blended the unique qualities and
attractions of the three destinations in special interest tours
under three primary themes, namely, history and culture, regional
gourmet delight and golf.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the next step will see the launch of the web site
on the three areas, which will feature maps of the region,
information about the transportation network, details of various
scenic spots.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey by the Hong Kong Tourist Association,
2.65 million overseas tourists visited Hong Kong, Macao and
Guangdong in 1997, representing a growth of more than 30 percent
over 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
