<HEADLINE> Moscow to Invite Japanese Premier in Fall as Scheduled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko said Tuesday that Moscow will invite Japan's next prime
minister to visit Moscow this fall as scheduled for a summit with
Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Japan have confirmed that the basis of friendly
bilateral relations has not changed despite political changes in
Japan, Kiriyenko told a news conference at the Japan National
Press Club.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto announced his
resignation on Monday to take responsibility for the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party's major setback in Sunday's House of
Councillors election.
</P>
<P>
The LDP is to chose a new president by July 21, and that person
will become the next Japanese prime minister as the party holds a
majority in the powerful House of Representatives (lower house).
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto had planned to make an official visit to Russia in
October.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin has pledged to give an answer
to Hashimoto's proposal, made at their informal summit at the
Japanese resort town of Kawana in April, to resolve a territorial
dispute between their countries when the Japanese premier visits
Moscow this fall.
</P>
<P>
The territorial dispute over a group of islands has prevented
the two countries from concluding a peace treaty since the former
Soviet Union seized the islands at the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko said he was satisfied with his trip to Japan and cited
Japan's agreement to cooperate in the development of energy in the
Russian Far East as one of the fruits of the visit.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko, winding up his two-day visit to Japan, has left for
Beijing for a working visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
