<HEADLINE> Australia, France Sign Visa Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Australia and France signed an
agreement here Tuesday, which allows their citizens to travel to
each other's territories without visas for visits of up to three
months.
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer, who signed the
agreement with Dominique Girard, French ambassador to Australia,
said the streamlined access would benefit some 200,000 Australians
who visited France and its overseas territories of New Caledonia
and French Polynesia on holidays or business each year.
</P>
<P>
"This means that Australians can now travel to European Union
countries without the need for a visa (for visits of up to three
months)," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
He said there had been strong growth in the number of French
tourist and business visitors to Australia in the past two years,
and the new arrangements should serve to maintain this pleasing
trend.
</P>
<P>
The announcement confirmed the often rocky relationship between
Australia and France had now fully recovered from the disastrous
low of 1995 when French nuclear testing led to an almost complete
rupture in ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
