<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close More Than One Percent Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares rose by more
than one percent Tuesday as financial markets reacted positively
to the political situation in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries closed up 35.6 points, or 1.31 percent, to
2,754.2.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the local share market was buoyed by optimism in
Japanese markets that the resignation of Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto may lead to a quicker fiscal response to the country's
ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index lifted 51.1 points, or 1.07 percent,
to 4,833.6 while the all resources index rallied 24.7 points, or
2.35 percent, to 1,076.4.
</P>
<P>
Major diversified miners posted significant gains, with
Australia's leading company BHP lifting 36 cents to 14.42
Australian dollars and Rio Tinto up 55 cents to 18.90 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion was also firmer, trading in Sydney at 291.40 U.S.
dollars, well up from 289.25 U.S. dollars at Monday night's close.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed 15.2 points, or 1.43 percent, higher at
1,074.8.
</P>
<P>
The banking index gained 65.9 points, or 1.1 percent, to
6,036.5. National Australia Bank gained 13.3 cents to 22.633
Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia lifted 18 cents
to 20.04 Australian dollars, Westpac bank rose 19.5 cents to
10.435 Australian dollars and ANZ bank lifted five cents to 11.32
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overall, national turnover totaled 23.296 million shares,
valued at 482.88 million U.S. dollars with rises outnumbering
falls 544 to 409. 
</P>
