<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Borrow to Recapitalize Local Banks: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia would borrow and use
local funds for the 16 billion ringgit (3.773 billion U.S.
dollars) needed to recapitalize local banks, Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have quite a lot of savings, for example the Employees'
Provident Fund with monthly contributions of 1.2 billion ringgit
(283 million U.S. dollars)," he told reporters after opening the
Universiti Kebangsaan (National University) Malaysia (UKM)
Hospital in Bandar Tun Razak, Cheras, near here.
</P>
<P>
He said part of the borrowings would be raised through bond
issues, some internationally while the rest domestically.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim said Monday 16 billion
ringgit (3.773 billion U.S. dollars) is required for the banking
system for 1998 and 1999 in order to maintain the risk-weighted
capital ratio at 9.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir also said his government may find other ways of
reducing interest rates without touching the base lending rate
(BLR). The government can reduce the BLR but if it does so, some
foreign companies might increase their interest rates, causing an
outflow of funds from Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He said another setback would be the possibility of currency
traders to further devalue ringgit as they might decide "this is
bad."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that the government hoped to further reduce the
BLR in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
