<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Mediates Ethio-Eritrean Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
has decided to meet Eritrean President Isaias Afewerki in
Nairobi later this week following his three-hour talks with
Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi Monday.
</P>
<P>
"President Moi will meet Mr. Afewerki sometime this week,"
a Kenyan Foreign Ministry official told Xinhua Tuesday. Moi's move
was seen the latest of a series of international mediation efforts
since border clashes erupted between Ethiopia and Eritrea on May 6.
</P>
<P>
"They will just consult with each other to find a solution,"
said the official who declined to tell his name.
</P>
<P>
Tensions escalated in early June when Ethiopia and Eritrea
bombed each other and battles raged for a brief period on three
fronts. Hundreds were killed before fighting gave way to a
stalemate on the border where thousands of troops have been
massed on each side.
</P>
<P>
In June, Eritrea rejected a proposal by the U.S. and Rwanda to
end the fighting. Further attempts by African heads of state
from Burkina Faso, Zimbabwe and Djibouti also made little
headway.
</P>
<P>
After talks with Zenawi who paid one-day visit to Nairobi, Moi
said that their discussions on the conflict "was not a new
initiative" but "would lend weight to the ongoing initiatives by
the OAU (Organization of African Unity) and other parties."
</P>
<P>
"It was proper and prudent (for Kenya) to take the territorial
dispute seriously since Ethiopia is Kenya's neighbor and a member
of Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD)," Moi said
in a statement issued after the talks.
</P>
<P>
Moi now chairs IGAD, which groups Kenya, Eritrea, Somalia,
Sudan, Uganda and Djibouti. The body was set up to help resolve
problems among member states in the Horn of Africa and east
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
