<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Conduct Pilot Census in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania plans to conduct a
pilot census on August 30 in preparation for a nationwide census
scheduled one year later, the Commissioner for Census has said.
</P>
<P>
The demographic project will be undertaken in a few selected
areas throughout the country with diversed social and economic
backgrounds, Commissioner for Census Damas Mbogoro said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The areas earmarked for the pilot census are places where a
particular class of people such as fishermen, livestock keepers,
miners, town dwellers and peasants predominate," Mbogoro said.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said that the census not only involves
counting the people, but also collects a lot of other social and
economic information.
</P>
<P>
He said that the pilot census also means for assessment of
training of enumerators which are expected to be around 56,000.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania, with a territory of 945,087 square kilometers,
carried three census in 1967, 1978 and 1988. Its population
has reportedly risen to about 30 million since last
census which registered 23.1 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
