<HEADLINE> Chinese-Korean Seminar on Neo-Confucians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUOYANG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A seminar on three Chinese
philsophers who had a great influence on Chinese thought has been
held in Luoyang, a historical city in central China's Henan
Province.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 scholars from China and the Republic of Korea
attended the two-day seminar and presented 29 papers on the
thought of Cheng Hao, Cheng Yi and Zhu Xi, representatives of the
Neo-Confucian school of thought in the Northern Song Dynasty
(960-1127).
</P>
<P>
The scholars say that the thinkers had the greatest influence
in feudal times after Confucius and Mencius. They held that all
things in the universe were determined by "reason", which had
existed before all things.
</P>
<P>
Some of the scholars say they will work to apply Zhu Xi's
teachings to traditional Chinese culture and the social sciences.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
