<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, July 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The Security Council of the United Nations
issued a presidential statement Monday condemning massacres and
other atrocities and violations of international humanitarian law
in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the council reviewed a recent report of the
UN Secretary General's aborted human rights investigation team in
the country. The report concludes that the killing by the Alliance
of Democratic Force for the Liberation of the Congo constituted
crimes against humanity. (Security Council-Congo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Former Italian former premier Silvio Berlusconi was
sentenced to two years and four months in jail Monday for illegal
party financing.
</P>
<P>
Berlusconi, 61, was also fined 10 billion lire (about 5.7
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The media magnate was alleged to have illegally channeled 22
billion lire (12.5 million dollars) to ex-premier Bettino Craxi
and his Socialist Party. (Italy-Berlusconi-Verdict)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Republic of Montenegro in Yugoslavia Monday
staged rallies to mark the 57th anniversary of the armed uprising
against fascist invaders.
</P>
<P>
Montenegro President Milo Djukanovic, military leaders such as
Ladoslav Martinovic and Milan Zec and World War II veterans joined
the rally held at Virpazar meeting center and laid wreaths at the
martyrs' tomb. (Yugoslavia-Montenegro-Anniversary)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- U.N. General Secretary Kofi Annan said Monday that
the Brazilian government's policies had set the country on course
for regaining economic stability.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived on July 11 in Brazil, was speaking at a
meeting with Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso in
Brasilia, the Brazilian political capital. (Brazil-Annan-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
