<HEADLINE> Australia Launches Program to Aid China in Public Sectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Agency for
International Development (AusAID) and the Chinese Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) launched the 20
million Australian dollar Capacity Building Program here today to
cooperate in strengthening selected Chinese public sectors.
</P>
<P>
The largest project funded so far under the technical
cooperation program between AusAID and MOFTEC, the Capacity
Building Program will support Chinese policy-making and program
implementation in key areas relating to the transition to a market
economy.
</P>
<P>
This is to be achieved through the transfer and adaptation of
leading-edge Australian systems and expertise, particularly in
sectors such as banking, finance, taxation, social security and
insurance, and urban planning and development.
</P>
<P>
Australian Ambassador to China Richard Campbell Smith
officiated the launching of the program, and said it "will
undoubtedly build a sense of partnership" between Australia and
China. He also noted its timeliness as China meets the challenges
of state-owned enterprise reforms and the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC Vice-minister Sun Zhenyu was present at the announcement
ceremony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
