<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discord on Pricing Delays W. African Gas Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The implementation of the
260-million-U.S.-Dollar west African gas pipeline project is
being delayed over the inability of the promoters to reach
agreement with gas suppliers on pricing.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, Ghana, Togo and Benin are jointly promoting the
project, while two of the world's leading oil companies, Shell
and Chevron, are poised to supply the pipeline system with
natural gas from the oil fields they operate in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The project has been seen as a major joint venture to promote
sub-regional cooperation in the economic field, as the pipeline
is expected to extend to cover the whole of west Africa in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Officials were already looking at an October date for the
start-up of the project after the completion of survey of gas
markets in Ghana, Togo and Benin by the West African Gas Pipeline
Company.
</P>
<P>
The major problem now is reaching agreement on the right price
at which the gas is to be delivered to these countries, the
Lagos-based Daily Times newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted company sources as saying that both Shell
and Chevron could raise the 260 million U.S. Dollars to fund the
project and that the firms must get agreement to sell the gas at
profitable rate.
</P>
<P>
But as the project suffers delay, more stumbling blocks lay
ahead as Ghana which is the prime mover of the project is
considering alternative sources to boost its electricity
generation.
</P>
<P>
To generate electricity is the major reason of Ghana for
promoting the sub-regional gas project.
</P>
<P>
The country has been carrying out an electricity rationing
program since the beginning of this year due to lack of electric
power supply.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Ghana has contracted Japanese and
American firms to supply very large gas storage vessel which
would be used to general electricity.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Ghana at the weekend settled its rift
with Burkina Faso over cut in water flow from the Volta River
which affected operations at Ghana's Akosombo Hydroelectric Power
Station.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed an agreement to work together to use
the resources of the Volta River.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
