<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Turkish newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Yeni Yuzyil (New Century):
</P>
<P>
-- At a press conference in the parliament Monday, Turkish
Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit suggested that the general
elections be held in November in order to create a stable
political environment as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and opposition Republican People's
Party Chairman Deniz Baykal agreed last month that the current
coalition government would resign at the end of this year and a
new "election government" would bring the country to early
elections next April.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel, who country is
currently holding the European Union (EU) rotating presidency,
said in Brussels Monday that the EU would make great efforts to
normalize its ties with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish-EU relations have remained tense since last
December when Ankara was excluded from the EU's enlargement
process at the EU summit in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Aksam (Evening):
</P>
<P>
-- Yilmaz said Monday that his government was determined to
bring down the soaring inflation rate, but stressed that "this
needs time."
</P>
<P>
Turkey's inflation rate, which stood at 80 percent at the end
of June, has become one of the major bottlenecks for its economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Cumhuriyet (Republic):
</P>
<P>
-- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his Cypriot counterpart
Glafcos Clerides, who was in Moscow on an official visit,
confirmed Monday that they would go ahead with the missile deal
as agreed despite strong opposition from Turkey and Turkish
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Turkish has vowed to take all necessary steps to prevent the
missiles from entering the divided island, saying the missile
deployment would constitute a direct threat to Turkey's state
security. The anti-aircraft Russian missiles are due to be
delivered next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
