<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,347 People Removed From Voter List in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's National Election
Committee has decided to remove 1,347 more people from the voter
list for reasons mainly of nationality.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced at the committee's daily press
briefing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Among those removed from the 5.4-million voter list, 1,298 were
from Phnom Penh who were all without proper documents to identify
their Cambodian nationality. The others, who were from Kandal and
Battambang provinces were deleted from the list because of death
and multiple registration.
</P>
<P>
The committee has so far removed nearly 2,000 people from the
voter list. Early last week 53 Vietnamese were removed from the
list and later on Saturday 393 others were struck out for reasons
including multiple registration.
</P>
<P>
Though the National Election Committee has been criticized for
some of its members' connection with the Cambodia People's Party,
the Coalition for Free and Fair Elections said Sunday the move
could be a sign that the committee may be serious about
eliminating election fraud. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 08:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Trade Deficit Shrinks in First Half of '98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Israel's trade deficit declined
by 22 percent in the first half of this year compared to the same
period last year, the Israeli Haaretz daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the Central Bureau of Statistics as saying
that the trade deficit stood at 3.4 billion U.S. dollars during
the first six months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The bureau attributed the deficit decline to the improved trade
balances with the United States and the European Union (EU),
Israel's two major trading partners.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit with the U.S. fell by a whopping 44 percent,
while that with the EU dropped by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the gains were partially offset by a 45 percent increase in
the trade deficit with Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The improved overall trade balance was largely caused by a 9 to
10 percent increase in total exports in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Exports, rising by 700 million dollars, stood at 8.4 billion
dollars. About half of the increase derived from exports to the
EU, which totaled 3.1 billion dollars; another 38 percent
consisted of exports to the U.S., which totaled 2.3 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Asia, in contrast, fell about 12 percent to 889
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports plunged by 2 percent in the first half of 1998 to 11.8
billion dollars. The imports from the U.S. and Europe decreased by
1.6 percent and 3.5 percent respectively, while the imports from
Asia rose by 3.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Is Most Important Trade Partner Of Eastern Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Even during the Asian financial
crisis east China's Shandong Province, which is close to the Republic
of Korea and Japan, still considered Asian countries its most
important trade partners.
</P>
<P>
Du Shicheng, vice-governor of the province, points to these
geographic advantages for trade relations and says the province
has gained a lot from them in the past, and the province is paying
a great deal of attention to protecting foreign-funded firms from
these countries.
</P>
<P>
An automobile project backed by Daewoo with 5.7 billion yuan,
for example, has begun construction after several months of
delays, with the help of the Chinese partners.
</P>
<P>
The province had a drop in exports and foreign investment, but
recent statistics show an export increase in the province of 0.1
percent in the first five months, and Du predicts that the
situation will get better in the second half, and points out that
the fourth quarter is the province's peak period for exports.
</P>
<P>
He says though that the province has to wait and see whether
the Japanese yen is depreciated, because foreign trade could be
hit severely.
</P>
<P>
Also, the province's foreign trade structure has to be changed
because it depends too heavily on the Asian market, with 27 percent
of its exports going to Japan and 23 percent to ROK, and it
exports too many raw materials and farm products, and too few
high-tech goods.
</P>
<P>
So the province has been trying to enter the European and
American markets and is providing subsidies for exports and
encouraging firms to improve technology to make their products
more competitive. It has also set up six teams to help
export-oriented firms do business overseas.
</P>
<P>
These efforts seem to be paying off. In the January-May period,
exports Europe and the United States were up 50 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Merapi Volcano Spews Hot Ashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Following the easing of warning in
the slopes of Mount Merapi, from full alert to high alert, the
most active volcano spewed lava and hot ashes four times early
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The spewing occurred from 00:00 to 6:00 a.m. Monday, Antara
News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The lava and toxic gases were flowing down westward about 3,000
meters from the crater to Lamat river, the report quoted a local
official as saying later Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mas Atje Purbawinata, head of the Yogyakarta volcanology
office, said Merapi's hot ashes would continue to threaten the
western slope of the volcano as lava and hot ashes were still
flowing down westward.
</P>
<P>
Seven villages in the western area of the volcano have been
considered as danger areas, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, no evacuation of the tens of thousands of residents
within an 11-kilometer radius that could be affected if the
situation continues to deteriorate, has been ordered.
</P>
<P>
The decision is up to the local government authorities, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
"But they have set up emergency command posts, and I have seen
them," he added.
</P>
<P>
Merapi, which overlooks the densely-populated southern plain of
Central Java, erupted last Saturday, with explosions that could be
heard as far as 20 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Lava spills flowed into river beds at the foot of the mountain
and some villages were reported to be under 1.5 meters of ash,
which also blanketed crops and plantations.
</P>
<P>
Merapi, 2,968-meter high, last erupted in 1994, killing more
than 60 people and forcing more than 6,000 others to evacuate to
safer grounds.
</P>
<P>
Merapi is one the 127 active volcanoes in Indonesia, a country
which lies along the so-called Pacific Ring of Fire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0199 </DOCNO>
