<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Surging in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed higher for the
second straight day in Tokyo Tuesday due to a last-minute buying
of bank and steel shares after fluctuating throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
But the key Nikkei index found little room to grow
significantly under the weight of selling pressure by institutions
and hesitance among investors to move until a successor is found
for Japanese Prime Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose 128.52
points, or 0.79 percent, from Monday's close to end at 16,488.91.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 10.21 points or 0.31 percent to
1,266.65.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section came to an estimated 400 million
shares, up slightly from 389.08 million shares Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was Tuesday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Analysts anticipate a dull market throughout the week following
Hashimoto's announcement Monday of his resignation to take the
blame for his Liberal Democratic Party's major setback in Sunday's
House of Councillors election.
</P>
<P>
The LDP is to chose a new president July 21, and that person
will become the next prime minister because of the party's
majority in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Investors are also still waiting for details about the size and
timing of next year's permanent income tax cuts, promised by
outgoing Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto to stimulate domestic
consumption.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
surpassed losers 747 to 378, with 146 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
