<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto resigned on Monday
after a crashing defeat suffered by his Liberal Democratic Party
in the election of the Senate. The incumbent foreign minister,
Keizo Obuchi, who is the main designer for improved relations with
Russia, is among the favorites to succeed Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
-- More than 600,000 people hailed the French football team who
came down on a bus on the Champs-Elysee Monday afternoon. After
one night of folly, France was living the euphoria as the
conqueror of the world football championship.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- July 12, the day when France won the World Cup, made up a
festival of national unity re-discovered. Suddenly, the crowd felt
themselves to be French. Our country has a soul, and perhaps it is
this singularity which expresses July 14, the French specialty.
</P>
<P>
L'Humanite:
</P>
<P>
-- Thank you football. With millions of voices, excited and
cheerful, France affirms itself as that of Kabylian Zidane,
Ariegeois Barthez, Guadeloupean Thuram, and Ghanaian Desailly. One
should think that Le Pen, who does not like these footballers, was
the biggest loser of the World Cup. 
</P>
