<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Amending Copyright Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- China is now amending its
seven-year-old copyright law in order to enhance copyright
protection and better align itself with international conventions.
</P>
<P>
A State Press and Publications Administration official today
told Xinhua that the amended copyright law will bridge the gap
between China's current copyright law and international
conventions, as well as tackle problems which appeared after the
issuance of the current copyright law in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The ammeded copyright law will also strengthen the protection
of new technologies such as databases and multimedia products, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Since it went into effect seven years ago," the official said,
"the current copyright law has played a significant role in
China's copyright protection, but due to a lack of experience, it
has some problems such as dual-standards for Chinese and
foreigners."
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the new law is demanded by
technological development. "Legal issues caused by new computer
technology and the Internet have caused wide concern among
legislators," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the amended draft of the copyright law is
expected to be submitted to the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
