<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Arrests Hundreds People for World Cup Gambling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A total of 593 Thais were arrested
for illegal gambling on the World Cup finals, local police said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Those detained included both gamblers and bookmakers, said an
officer with a task-force set up to combat betting on the
tournament that ended Sunday with France beating Brazil 3-0 for
World Cup title.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a survey by a major research group found spending by
Bangkok residents on eating out, entertainment and transport was
slashed as Thais stayed home to watch the games, which were
screened late at night because of the time difference with France.
</P>
<P>
Spending on newspapers increased dramatically as Thais sought
out the blanket coverage given to the World Cup, rising 26.03
percent to an average of 92 baht a week,
</P>
<P>
Another positive effect of the tournament was that traffic flow
had markedly improved, the survey noted, adding spending on
petrol was down 10.63 percent as people stayed at home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
