<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists: Western Diet Linked to Colon Cancer Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Western diets rich in meat and
low in fruits may increase the risk of colon cancer, American
scientists warned in a study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The dietary pattern associated with the greatest increase in
risk is the one which typifies a Western-style diet," Dr. Martha
Slattery of the University of Utah Medical Center wrote in the
latest issue of the American Journal of Epidemiology.
</P>
<P>
Slattery and his colleagues used detailed questionnaires to
ascertain the long-term eating patterns of nearly 4,400 American
adults. Half of them were colon cancer patients and the other half
were healthy "Controls."
</P>
<P>
The researchers found that men and women who ate a "Western"
diet -- high in red and processed meats, refined grains and
sugars, and low in fresh fruits and vegetables -- doubled their
overall risk for colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
This type of diet was also strongly associated with higher
daily cholesterol and energy intake, weight gain, and obesity.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, those who ate a "prudent" diet -- low in red meat
and sugars but high in fish, poultry, fresh fruits and vegetables
-- achieved a nearly 40 percent reduction in their colon cancer
risk.
</P>
<P>
These individuals also exercised more and had an average lower
body weight than those on more "Western" diets.
</P>
<P>
According to the American Cancer Society, colon cancer kills
over 46,000 people every year in the United States, making it the
country's second leading cause of cancer death after lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
Experts were said to have long speculated that certain foods
and diets may influence colon cancer risk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0218 </DOCNO>
