<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman on Resignation of Japanese PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman
Tang Guoqiang said here today that China has taken note of the
Japanese Upper House election that has just been held and hoped
that the country's political situation will remain stable.
</P>
<P>
Tang made the statement at a news conference here this
afternoon when asked about the resignation of Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto after the election.
</P>
<P>
He said that the establishment and development of long-term,
stable good-neighborly friendly ties between China and Japan
comply with the fundamental interest of the two countries and
their people, and are also beneficial to peace and development in
the Asia-Pacific region and the whole world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
He said that this year, the 20th anniversary of the signing of
China-Japan Peace and Friendship Treaty, is in a pivotal period
for bilateral ties. "We believe joint efforts of the two sides
will further push forward the development of Sino-Japanese ties,"
he pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
