<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Enact Chemical Weapons Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
soon enact a convention that prohibits the development,
production, stockpiling and use of chemical weapons, local press
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The convention will be ratified following an agreement between
all four factions at the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
At a House plenary meeting here Monday, all factions said the
government will enact the convention "to maintain world peace".
</P>
<P>
The discussion of the enactment of the convention commenced on
June 29 when Foreign Affairs Minister Ali Alatas proposed that
Indonesia join global efforts to ban chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has signed the convention on chemical weapons on
January 13, 1993.
</P>
<P>
Alatas told the House Monday that the convention on chemical
weapons essentially aims to protect humans from the threat of
chemical warfare.
</P>
<P>
The convention is not the final goal, but is an instrument that
can be used to achieve the honorable goal of protecting all
mankind, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that after the convention is enacted by the
president, the government will submit the document to United
Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
He was quick to reassure the House that passing the convention
would not hurt the country's industries that produce or import
various chemicals.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia will not meet any obstacles in the trade of chemical
materials needed to develop the national economy," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
