<HEADLINE> Iran Condemns Israeli Air Raids on South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Foreign Ministry spokesman
Mahmoud Mohammadi Tuesday condemned the Israeli air raids on
residential quarters in south Lebanon Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said the Israeli attacks violated all international
conventions and were also evidence of "the terrorist substance" of
the Jewish state, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Two Irish members of the U.N. peacekeepers and a Lebanese
civilian were wounded when an Israeli warplane fired two missiles
Monday at the Hataida village, a stronghold of the Iranian-backed
Shiite Muslim guerrilla group Hezbollah (Party of God) in the
central sector of the Israeli-occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
Under the ceasefire agreement signed between Israel and the
Hezbollah in April 1996 after the Israeli Operation Grapes of
Wrath, both sides agreed to avoid attacking civilian targets or
using civilian cover in carrying out military operations.
</P>
<P>
Since the Islamic Revolution in 1979, Iran has been supporting
the Lebanese resistance groups, especially the Hezbollah, in their
fight to oust the Israeli occupation troops.
</P>
<P>
Israel has carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon since 1985 with the claimed aim to protect its
northern areas from guerrilla cross-border attacks. 
</P>
