<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 06:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaitis With Dual Nationality May Lose Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 14 (Xinhua) -- About 18,500 Kuwaiti citizens
may soon lose the government housing for holding a second
nationality, local English daily Arab Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A recommendation for withdrawing houses from such citizens was
recently adopted by top government authorities, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Nationality Law, enacted in 1959, stipulates that "Kuwaiti
citizens shall not hold the citizenship of any other country."
</P>
<P>
The Public Authority for Housing Care has begun studying files
of citizens who are enjoying government housing despite their
dual nationality.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ministry of Finance has also begun circulating a
confidential letter to state ministries and institutions to ask
for detailed reports on such citizens.
</P>
<P>
The government took the actions after it received complaints
that these citizens live mostly abroad but return to Kuwait every
six months to benefit from state-rendered privileges, such as
monthly salaries and free medical service.
</P>
<P>
These citizens also lease their homes to others while many
Kuwaiti families are anxiously waiting for government housing,
according to the charges.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti government is now serious about instituting legal
proceedings against citizens who abuse Kuwaiti nationality by
using it merely as a source of financial gains and housing
benefits, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
