<HEADLINE> No More Foreign Banks to Open Business in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- No foreign banks will be allowed to
open business in Bangladesh in the near future, said the country's
central bank, Bangladesh Bank.
</P>
<P>
But foreign banks would get permission to set up leasing
businesses in the country, Lutfar Rahman Sarkar, governor of
Bangladesh Bank, was quoted as saying by The Financial Express
daily Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Applications for opening businesses by three foreign banks were
pending, and they were unlikely to be considered soon, according
to bank sources, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
There are about 40 banks operating in Bangladesh, including 13
foreign banks which account for over 6 percent of the business in
the country's banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Local banks, particularly national commercial banks in
Bangladesh, are facing fierce competition from their foreign
counterparts both in terms of business and services.
</P>
<P>
Foreign banks are in a better position in terms of efficient
management, technological development, network support, proper
accountability and independent lending.
</P>
<P>
It takes little time for them to adapt to advanced banking
operations and then provide better services, but local banks, slow
to respond to new technological innovations, are not even able to
introduce ATM, credit card and instant fund transfer, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
