<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Defends Right to Seize Illegal Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has asserted its right
to seize any vessel that enters its territorial waters without
permission, the Arab Times daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber
Al-Sabah was quoted as saying Monday that his country was ready to
detain ships that violate the U.N. sanctions on Iraq by entering
Kuwait's waters.
</P>
<P>
Sabah was commenting on the seizure of two foreign ships
recently by the Kuwaiti Coast Guard, the English-language daily
said.
</P>
<P>
The two dhows, which were registered in India and the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) respectively, were sailing from Iraq to the
UAE carrying a cargo of dates and sheep skin.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has imposed trade embargo on Iraq
since 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Nouri Saad, assistant director of Kuwait Port Authority, said
Kuwait has the legal right to confiscate and sell the cargo, and
have the vessels sold.
</P>
<P>
The proceeds would be used to cover the penalty fees, customs
fees and costs of towing the vessels into port, he added.
</P>
<P>
Saad said the 15 Indian crew on board have been questioned and
are kept at the port of Doha near Kuwait City.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Kuwait has seized six vessels so far this
year, but none of them has been sold due to the complicated
process of selling such vessels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
