<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Family Income, Expenditures Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Total family income increased by
65.8 percent in 1997 in the Philippines to 1.758 trillion pesos
(42 pesos to one U.S. dollar at current rate) over the 1.061
trillion pesos in 1994, the National Statistics Office said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A survey released by the office showed total family
expenditures reached 1.422 trillion pesos, which was 64.8 percent
higher over the 863 billion pesos in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Adjusting for the 23.1 percent inflation between 1994 and 1997,
total family income grew by 34.6 percent while total family
expenditures moved up by 33.8 percent, it showed.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of the national income came from wages and salaries
with proportion to total income pegged at 45.2 percent in 1997
which was higher than the 44 percent share in 1994.
</P>
<P>
It also showed that wages and salaries from non-agricultural
sources increased from 40 percent to 42.1 percent while wages and
salaries from the agriculture sector went down from 4 percent to 3
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
