<HEADLINE> Egg-Size Blue Sapphire Found in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A proprietary gem miner in Sri
Lanka's gem-mining district of Ratnapura last week found a
precious 880-carat blue sapphire the size of an egg, according
local newspaper reports Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Its value is yet to be estimated but Gem Authority officials
said it is worth at least 800,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka is known as an "island of gems" and historical
evidence shows that gems were an important product for trade
during early times.
</P>
<P>
Ratnapura or city of gems, more than 100 kilometers from
Colombo, has been the center for the country's gem industry for
many years.
</P>
<P>
The recipient of the gem, Leela Dharmadasa, Monday evening
showed the stone to President Chandrika Kumaratunga at her
official residence, saying the stone will assist her in making a
fortune and hoping this will be the start of a new era where more
stones of this weight, quality and magnitude would be found.
</P>
<P>
In previous instances where valuable gems were found they were
sold in the black market owning to the prevailing tariff system.
Gem miners now have the opportunity to sell their valuable gems at
auction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
