<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Security Council Condemns Massacres in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of the
United Nations issued a presidential statement on Monday
condemning massacres and other atrocities and violations of
international humanitarian law in the Democratic Republic of the
Congo.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the council reviewed a recent report of the
UN Secretary General's aborted human rights investigation team in
the country. The report concludes that the killing by the Alliance
of Democratic Force for the Liberation of the Congo constituted
crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
The report finds possible evidence of genocide, noting that
attacks on camps in north Kivu in 1996 "reveal the intent to
eliminate those Rwandan Hutus who had remained in former Zaire."
</P>
<P>
The UN Secretary General Kofi Annan withdrew the team in April
because of a total lack of cooperation from the government of the
Democratic Republic of the Congo. The team had gone in with a
mandate to investigate violations of human rights and
international humanitarian law, which were alleged to have been
committed in the country up to December 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the council recognized the necessity to
further investigate the massacres, other atrocities and violations
of international humanitarian law and to prosecute those
responsible.
</P>
<P>
The council called on the governments of the Democratic
Republic of the Congo and Rwanda to investigate without delay, in
their respective countries, allegations contained in the report of
the investigation team and to bring to justice any persons found
to have been involved in the massacres, atrocities and violations
of international humanitarian law.
</P>
<P>
The council encouraged the governments of the Democratic
Republic of the Congo and Rwanda to seek international assistance,
such as technical assistance, in this process.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council expressed its readiness to consider, as
necessary in light of actions by the governments of the two
countries, additional steps to ensure that perpetrators of the
massacres, other atrocities and violations of international
humanitarian law were brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
It expressed support for United Nations' and other
international activity in reducing ethnic tensions and promoting
national reconciliation in the region, and encouraged governments
concerned to continue to cooperate in these activities to bring
about a real improvement in the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
