<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka May Not Sign Military Accord With U.S.: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is unlikely to sign the
Status of Forces Agreement (SOFA) with the United States, a report
of the national news agency BSS said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Bangladesh has nothing to gain by signing the SOFA. Rather, it
(SOFA) would be detrimental to the national interest," the news
agency quoted a "competent source" at the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs as saying.
</P>
<P>
"National interest will be above everything" while entering
into any agreement with any country, big or small, on any issue,
be it on economic matters or military affairs, the source said.
</P>
<P>
The prospect of signing the SOFA is "bleak" although "we have
close cooperation with the U.S. in many fields including the area
of defense," the source said.
</P>
<P>
"No countries in South Asia, Southeast Asia and the Middle East
except Israel signed this treaty with the U.S.," the source
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The proposed agreement would provide for entry of U.S. troops
into Bangladesh without passport and visa, but no such reciprocal
facilities would be given to Bangladeshi defense personnel going
to the United States for training and other purposes, according to
the source.
</P>
<P>
As a member of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC), Bangladesh has a responsibility for the
region as a whole and could not allow entry of foreign troops into
the region which might have "profound and far-reaching
consequences," it added.
</P>
<P>
Stationing of foreign troops in or frequent entry of alien
forces into the country might have an adverse impact. "We don't
see any reasonable ground or need to have an umbrella agreement
like the SOFA," it said.
</P>
<P>
Americans desirous of entering Bangladesh to carry out relief
operations, or for military exercises or for other legitimate
purposes could do so through a memorandum of understanding (MOU)
on a case-by-case basis. "We can have as many MOUs as required,"
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Besides visa-free entry for U.S. troops, other clauses such as
those providing unrestricted movement for American troops in the
country and the entry of equipment and supplies carried by U.S.
troops without undergoing customs clearances are not acceptable to
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
"Allowing entry of weapons and equipment in the country without
customs duty is against the law of the country and it will require
constitutional amendment," the sources explained.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has military cooperation with a number of countries,
including India, Pakistan, Thailand, Britain, Austria and the
United States, but only the United States has proposed such an
agreement, the source added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
