<HEADLINE> General Motors Recalling One Million Cars to Fix Air Bags </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, July 13 (Xinhua) -- General Motors Corp. announced
Monday that it is recalling nearly one million cars because their
air bags may deploy by accident.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after 161 injuries were registered from
301 reports of air bags inadvertently deploying.
</P>
<P>
Among the 966,000 recalled cars, the company said, there are
863,000 GM Chevrolet Cavaliers and Pontiac Sunfires from the 1996
and 1997 model years, and 103,000 Cadillac DeVille, Seville and
Eldorado from model year 1995.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to the U.S. National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration (NHTSA), General Motors said the recall will begin
in August and dealers will change the software programing in the
air bag computer so the air bag does not inflate in less forceful
collisions.
</P>
<P>
There are about 75 million vehicles on the U.S. road with
driver-side air bags, and about 47 million also have
passenger-side air bags.
</P>
<P>
NHTSA has received reports that 108 people have been killed by
air bags, including 63 children, according to government records.
</P>
<P>
The administration is also investigating reports of similar
problems concerning Chrysler minivans and cars, Subarus, Mazdas
and Volvos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
