<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Enters Online Real-estate Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft launched its new
HomeAdvisor service on Monday, offering nationwide real-estate
listings, plus photos, maps and lending information.
</P>
<P>
HomeAdvisor is not expected to make a profit soon, but the
service is a way to gain a foothold in a business many think will
become profitable in the future.
</P>
<P>
By making it easier to find homes for sale and arrange loan
services over the Web, Microsoft hopes to capture a chunk of the
mortgage fee market, a business worth seven billion U.S. dollars
annually.
</P>
<P>
While receiving a commission, Microsoft hopes to generate
revenue from advertising and from sponsorship fees from companies
selling products to home buyers.
</P>
<P>
The depth of data varies from home to home. Some include
pictures and detailed structural descriptions, others just mention
the number of bedrooms and bathrooms. The software company
promises daily updates and hopes to persuade companies to offer
richer, more complete information.
</P>
<P>
HomeAdvisor also offers services such as a calculator that
compares renting with buying, a neighborhood finder based on
school, crime and demographic data and an e-mail feature that
notifies its subscribers when interest rates reach a certain point
or a property becomes available.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft competitors include already-established online
home-finding services, loan providers and financial services.
</P>
<P>
A recent National Association of Realtors survey found that 18
percent of buyers in the United States searched for a house on the
Internet in the second half of 1997. But only two percent of them
eventually bought homes during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft has already been offering online services for booking
air tickets and buying cars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
