<HEADLINE> Kazakhs Urged to Guard Against World Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The central government of
Kazakhstan has asked local governments to take preventive measures
against any adverse impact of the ongoing international financial
crisis on the national economy.
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum on consolidating economic stability, the
central government on Saturday ordered leaders at all levels to
make efforts to increase budgetary revenues and reduce
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
The international financial crisis has led to a crude oil price
drop on the world market, which reduced tax income for the
government, the memorandum said.
</P>
<P>
The government has decided to lower tax rates of crude oil and
oil products to encourage exports of these products.
</P>
<P>
It will continue to improve tax collection and the work of the
customs besides establishing a national taxpayer registration
system.
</P>
<P>
To cut back public spendings, the government also imposed
consumption restrictions on mobile telephones, business travels,
refurbishing of offices, transportation and energy.
</P>
<P>
The number of civil servants will be slashed before September 1
on the basis of a national survey and the construction of non-key
projects will be suspended to reduce the burden on national
budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
