<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Urges ASEAN to Seek Common Identity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai has stressed the need to promote the common identity of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in order to
strengthen the sense of community within the grouping.
</P>
<P>
"We all have our national identities, but I believe we should
also try to promote a common regional identity as well," Chuan
told the on-going Fifth Conference of ASEAN Information Ministers
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by Tuesday's Nation newspaper as reiterating that
this sense of common identity will help foster a stronger sense of
community as well as increased ASEAN awareness.
</P>
<P>
"This sense of belonging is necessary if ASEAN is to move
forward as a single community, thus meeting the objectives of our
founding fathers," he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN, he said, needs to achieve better understanding among
their peoples through promotion of media links and improved
knowledge among technocrats and grassroots organizations about
ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said free flow of information will make the world a more
open society, in which ASEAN will also be inspired.
</P>
<P>
In the ASEAN Vision 2020, the organization's leaders envisage
vibrant and open societies consistent with their respective
national identities, where all people enjoy equitable access to
opportunities for total human development regardless of gender,
race, religion, language and social and cultural background.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, Chuan said, does not restrict access to outside news
and information and its government is fully committed to the
increased transparency and free flow of information.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand wants to export news and information to the
outside world and expressed the wish to see other countries in the
region make more use of news emanating from Thailand.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
