<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Reiterates Missile-Supply Promise to Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
reiterated on Monday his country's promise to provide Cyprus with
S-300 anti-aircraft missiles, a Russian presidential aide said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin repeated the promise during a meeting with visiting
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides, who began a tour in Moscow on
July 11 as a guest of honor at the World Youth Games, Yeltsin's
aide for international issues Sergei Prikhodyko said.
</P>
<P>
Prikhodyko said that the two presidents discussed bilateral
ties and also ways to resolve the dispute between the
internationally recognized Cyprus government of the mainly Greek
south of the island and the Turkish north.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents said they were willing to improve economic
ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed satisfaction with their common ground on
way to resolve the Cyprus issue, reaffirming their position on the
supply of the S-300s to Cyprus by Russia, which are scheduled to
be delivered next month.
</P>
<P>
Prikhodyko noted that military cooperation was an element in
the two countries' relations.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot President's trip followed a visit by Defense
Minister Yiannakis Omirou from July 7 to 10, who held talks with
his Russian counterpart Igor Dmitriyevich Sergeyev on
technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops took over the northern
part of the island in the aftermath of a failed coup by Greek
Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government, echoed by a Russian Foreign Ministry
official, has declared that the missile deal could be cancelled if
progress is achieved in reaching a peaceful settlement, for
example, on the island's demilitarization.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the Turkish Cypriots and Greek Cypriots
broke down last summer when Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
walked out in protest at European Union's intention to open
accession talks with the Cypriot government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
