<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines, Malaysia Sign Bilateral Payment Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and Malaysia have
signed a pioneering bilateral trade payment scheme that would
reduce the two countries' reliance on dollars, a leading newspaper
revealed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement is just an initial step," the Philippine Daily
Inquirer quoted Philippine Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, I think it sends an important signal that we are
deeply committed to fostering international trade through
innovative arrangements despite the current regional crisis,"
Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Singson said it was the first bilateral arrangement of its kind
forged among the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
member countries.
</P>
<P>
It involves regularly netting out over two-month periods export
and import transactions accumulated between the two countries
within accounts to be maintained by their central banks.
</P>
<P>
Although the net transactions will still be settled by the
respective central banks in U.S. dollars, the bilateral scheme is
seen to reduce the volume of actual monetary transfers between the
two countries and potentially save on transaction costs.
</P>
<P>
The government believes that the new arrangement would further
stimulate bilateral trade with Malaysia, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Total bilateral trade between the two countries stood at about
1.6 billion U.S. dollars in 1997 and has been increasing by 34
percent during the last three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inspections to Ensure Teaching Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The state will enhance performance
inspections of education departments and school authorities to
ensure students are receiving efficient instruction, said today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The inspections will include public supervision more often to
ensure fair practices are used, according to Guo Zhenyou, director
of the Department for Educational Inspection under the Ministry of
Education.
</P>
<P>
Educational inspections have been carried out for 10 years and
have helped improve compulsory and secondary education. China has
22,831 educational inspectors -- administrators who know the
education laws, regulations and situations.
</P>
<P>
Numerous inspections have been carried out in China regarding
implementation of the Compulsory Education Law, anti-illiteracy
campaigns and popularization of the nine-year compulsory
education, Guo said.
</P>
<P>
The inspections played an important role in improving teachers'
working and living conditions, stopping inconsistent fee
collections in some schools, easing students' heavy homework
burdens and building and revamping school buildings, he said.
</P>
<P>
Educational inspections resumed in China in 1986 when the
government issued the Compulsory Education law, Guo noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
