<HEADLINE> Ground Subsidence Emerges in Mexico City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Parts of Mexico City are
sinking into the ground by up to 28 centimeters a year, according
to a latest survey by the federal environmental protection agency.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the most serious subsidence happened in the
downtown area, where skyscrapers and ancient buildings are
located. In some areas, the surface even sank by more than 120
centimeters.
</P>
<P>
The agency attributed the subsidence to the over-tapping of
groundwater. The city taps 1.3 billion cubic meters each year.
</P>
<P>
City authorities have mapped out a strategic action plan to
curb the overuse of groundwater and are urging residents to save
water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
