<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First BOT Waterworks Project Inked in Chengdu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- China's first water supply BOT
(build, operate and transfer) project will be built in Chengdu,
capital of southwest China's Sichuan Province, according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
A construction agreement on the 100 million U.S. dollars
project was signed in Chengdu on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Parties to the agreement were: the Chengdu municipal
government; the Generale des Eaux Group of France, the world's
biggest urban water supply infrastructure supplier; and the
Marubeni Corp. of Japan.
</P>
<P>
This is the first urban water infrastructural project approved by
the central government to experiment with the use of foreign funds
under the BOT plan, said Wang Rongxuan, mayor of Chengdu, at the
signing ceremony for the agreement of Chengdu No. 6 Water Plant B
BOT project.
</P>
<P>
The project involves construction of a water plant in Chengdu
with a capacity of 400,000 tons of clean water a day and
construction of a 27-km-long water pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Official construction is scheduled before March 1999. After
completion, which is expected before September 2001, the Chengdu
municipal government will purchase 400,000 tons of clean water a
day from the plant, according to You Zhiyi, deputy chief of the
Chengdu Municipal Public Utilities Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The water project will ease the increasing pressure of
Chengdu's urban water supply capacity, said You. With a population
of nearly 3.2 million, the city has four water plants which
produce an average of 1.05 million tons of tap water a day. But
demand for water supply is increasing by 10 to 15 percent per
year. More water plants are needed.
</P>
<P>
A company jointly set up by the General des Eaux Group and the
Marubeni Corp will be responsible for the Chengdu No. 6 Water
Plant B BOT project's investment, construction, operation and
maintenance. After owning the plant for 18 years, the company will
transfer it to the Chengdu municipal government free of charge,
said Daniel Caille, president of the General des Eaux Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0276 </DOCNO>
