<HEADLINE> Economic Briefs from Latin America  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are brief
economic news items from Latin-America in the past week.
</P>
<P>
Managua -- The World Bank has granted two non-interest credits
totalling 71.4 million U.S. dollars to Nicaragua, of which 47.4
million will be used to improve highways and the rest will help
modernize the health system.
</P>
<P>
The credits will be paid back in 40 years, including a 10 years
grace period.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
Montevideo -- Wine exports by Uruguay had a 69 percent increase
in the first semester of 1998, compared with same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Viticulture National Institute of Uruguay said the country
placed on the international market 487,745 liters of wine up to
June 30, 197,924 liters more than that in the corresponding period
last year.
</P>
<P>
England imported 167,476 liters of wines from the South
American nation, followed by Norway, Denmark, Brazil, France,
Germany, Sweden, and Canada.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
Santa Fe de Bogota -- Colombia is to hold the annual fair of
footwear, leather, and morocco goods in Medellin from July 13 to
July 15. More than 270 national entrepreneurs will participate in
the fair.
</P>
<P>
The Footwear Manufacturers National Corporation says the annual
average shoes output in Colombia is 70 million pairs.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
Santa Fe de Bogota -- Siemens will invest 10 million dollars in
Colombia to develop the Energy and Telecommunications sectors.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Siemens Colombia Company's sales resulted in 4.835
billion pesos (about 3.61 million dollars) profits.
</P>
