<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EMS Reaches All the World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- China's express mail service (EMS)
is now linked to more than 200 countries and regions, reaching
nearly 2,000 cities across the globe, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
EMS has delivered 300 million pieces of mail, creating a
turnover of 11 billion yuan (1.33 U.S. dollars), since its
establishment on July 15, 1980.
</P>
<P>
EMS ranks third in the world for the number of pieces it
processes annually, behind the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Customers can call the "185" hotline, established last year,
for door-to-door mail collection service, business information,
EMS mail inquiries and to register complaints.
</P>
<P>
Domestic "overnight" delivery will be established by the end of
1999 between Beijing and major provincial capitals, between a
capital and other cities within its province, and between a city
and counties under it.
</P>
<P>
Overnight delivery is now available between Hong Kong and 10
inland cities, including Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Shenzhen
and Xiamen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
