<HEADLINE> Argentina's Trade Surplus Drops with Mercosur Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 13 (xinhua) -- Argentine had a trade surplus
of 120 million U.S. dollars in its trade with three other Mercosur
countries in the first five months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The surplus was 701 million dollars less than that in the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, Clarin reported that in January to May,
Argentina exported 3.38 billion dollars worth of goods to Brazil,
Paraguay and Uruguay, the three Southern Common Market (Mercosur)
countries, six percent less than in the same period of 1997, while
imports increased by 18 percent to 3.26 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The fall of oil prices resulted in the reduction of Argentina's
trade surplus when its oil exports to Brazil went down 54 percent.
</P>
<P>
In trade with the United States, Canada and Mexico, Argentina
registered a deficit of 1.95 billion dollars. It also had a trade
deficit of 1.19 billion dollars with the European Union and 84
million dollars with Southeast Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
