<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Academy to Emphasize Academics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The prestigious Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences (CASS) has decided to emphasize academics rather
than focusing on "minor practical problems."
</P>
<P>
Li Tieying, the academy's newly appointed president, has told
the institute's 3,000 scholars the study of basic theories must be
strengthened and other achievements should be a result of this
fundamental work.
</P>
<P>
"It cannot be called in-depth research if we merely make
suggestions for decision-makers without studying basic theories,"
said Li, a member of the Political Bureau of the Communist Party
of China Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Li replaced former president Hu Sheng, a well-known Marxist
historian, in March of this year.
</P>
<P>
The CASS, established in 1977, is regarded as the
central government think tank. In recent years, many of its
scholars have been engaged in designing China's reform and
opening-up.
</P>
<P>
Generally, programs that target hot economic and social topics
are easily granted subsidies. Some people have worried that this
trend might be too practical, and that "abstract and boring
subjects," such as archeology and anthropology, will be ignored.
</P>
<P>
Li said that practical research should be stepped up, but it
must deal with strategic and overall issues concerning the
nation's development.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the CASS told Xinhua that some research
programs engaged in by certain institutes with the goal of serving
government and Party leaders appear too short-sighted, and that
these programs do not reflect the major function of the
CASS.
</P>
<P>
He said the CASS has a limited capability for studying some
practical problems concerning government departments, especially
in the field of information gathering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Tomb Found in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have discover
an ancient tomb dating back some 1,700 years to the Western Jin
Dynasty (265-316) in Guilin, a tourism city in south China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The tomb, built in 307, has an arched roof and is 3.4 meters
long, 1.4 meters wide and 0.6 meter high, according to the
archeologists.
</P>
<P>
Experts have recovered pieces of porcelain and several special
bricks carved with Chinese characters indicating the year of
construction.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists say the discovery will provide valuable
clues for further research concerning the history and
development of the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
