<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pak Government Faces Herculean Task </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is teetering on the
brink of a financial meltdown as the much-needed external sources
of aid and assistance have now almost dried up due to the
sanctions triggered by the detonation of nuclear devices.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, with its economy much dependent on the foreign
assistance, faces an imminent default situation by the end of this
month as foreign exchange reserves evaporate and new foreign
exchange income is blocked owing to the freezing of its foreign
currency accounts.
</P>
<P>
To avoid a default, Pakistan needs nearly 5 billion U.S.
dollars a year to meet interest repayments on its hefty 36 billion
dollar foreign debt, including 1 billion dollars for interest
repayments in the third quarter of this year (July to September)
alone.
</P>
<P>
With a mere foreign exchange reserve of less than 800 million
dollars, which has already been reduced by 500 million dollars
since the nuclear tests at the end of May, Pakistan is facing an
arduous task to service its debt.
</P>
<P>
It is feared that Pakistan might be forced to declare a partial
moratorium on its debt repayments in less than a month if
international financial institutions like the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank withheld the release of
agreed loans as a penalty for its nuclear tests on May 28.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz said that about 1.2 billion
dollars in multilateral assistance due between June to September
this year was locked in sanctions imposed by some western
countries.
</P>
<P>
Under this situation, the finance minister said, Pakistan will
face balance of payments difficulties in two to three months if
the international financial institutions did not release the
committed funds.
</P>
<P>
At the end of this month, Pakistan will have to pay roughly 800
million dollars toward its huge dollars debt. Without
international assistance, that amount of payment will wipe out
Pakistan's foreign exchange reserves, leaving this South Asian
nation of 130 million people with no money to pay for imports.
</P>
<P>
The IMF sent a fact-finding mission last week to Islamabad and
held extensive talks with the Pakistani government. It was the
first visit to Pakistan by an IMF team since Pakistan conducted
nuclear tests at the end of May in the wake of similar tests by
its neighbor India in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
Paul Chabrier, IMF director for the Middle East region,
appreciated the progress made by Pakistan in the last 15 months in
respect of the economy and in implementing important structural
policies.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, although the economic performance has
improved, the release of funds also depends on the outlook of what
is forthcoming in external financing. In this area, he said, the
G-7, the donor countries, have an influential say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Congress to Ratify CTBT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- United States President Bill
Clinton on Monday urged the U.S. Senate to ratify the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Brazil's ratification of the treaty, which was
approved by the United Nations assembly in September 1996 and has
been signed by 149 countries, Clinton reaffirmed his call to the
Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
"I call on the Senate to act expeditiously to approve the
CTBT... so that the United States can lead in this vital
endeavor," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president spoke highly of Brazil's approval of the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
"Brazil's decision renews momentum for the international effort
to halt the spread of nuclear weapons and promote disarmament
around the world," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"At a time when actions by India and Pakistan threaten a
nuclear competition in South Asia, Brazil has chosen a different
course -- to invest in its people, not in a costly arms race," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress has refused to ratify the nuclear test ban
treaty several times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pak Government Faces Herculean Task </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The relations between the IMF and Pakistan have strained
following
sanctions slapped by G-8 member countries (including Russia) when
Islamabad opted to go nuclear in response to earlier Indian
nuclear
tests.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions spurred the IMF to postpone the further release
of
loans to Pakistan despite the fact that Pakistan had qualified for
it
by meeting all the macroeconomic targets set by the IMF. The delay
in
the release created serious problems for Pakistan since its
balance
of payments position is precarious.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistan government asked the IMF to fulfill its commitment
to
a three-year 1.6 billion dollar balance of payments support to
Islamabad since it had met all the conditions set by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Admitting for the first time that the economy was unlikely to
withstand the pressure of sanctions, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
has
written a letter to leaders of G-7 countries emphasizing the need
for
immediate restoration of support from international financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
After explaining the circumstances that led to the exercise of
the
nuclear option by Pakistan, Sharif emphasized that since Pakistan
had
successfully implemented the ESAF/Eff (Extended Structural
Adjustment
Facility/Extended Fund Facility) program, it would only be fair
for
donors to continue with the program.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports the IMF has asked Pakistan to sign
the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) to get the loan suspended by
the
Washington-based agency under pressure from G-8 countries.
</P>
<P>
So far Pakistan has refused to succumb to the United States and

sign the CTBT. "Islamabad wants international guarantees for the
peaceful solution of the core issue of Kashmir in accordance with
the
U.N. resolutions," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
Unless the international community promised to play its role
effectively in the resolution of the Kashmir dispute Pakistan
would
not budge an inch, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here are of the view that the present situation is
grim
and may become grimmer still if, in retaliation, the international

sanctions are tightened and enforced with full force.
</P>
<P>
Already remittances have almost dried up because of the wide
differential between official and unofficial rates of foreign
exchange.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, this South Asian nation remains in the grip of
panic.
The stock market index has dipped to a record low because of
eroding
confidence of investors. Inflation, on the other hand, is also
expected to rise significantly in the near future.
</P>
<P>
This is the situation which the Pakistani government has to
face
whether it has been engineered abroad or created by itself.
</P>
<P>
The government has now been left with very few options in the
post-nuclear test economic scenario. If loans from international
financial institutions are not resumed immediately, the choice
left
to the government is either to declare an immediate moratorium on
its
foreign debt, or do nothing until its foreign exchange reserves
are
totally depleted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
