<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Stages Games Opening Ceremony, Wins Four Golds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia staged a grand opening
ceremony of the World Youth Games Monday night, showcasing its
multi-ethnic culture and high technology marked by the Mir space
station and expertise to stop rain.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, International Olympic
Committee President Juan Samaranch, and Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov
attended the two-hour extravaganza along with some 60,000
specataors and athletes.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin wished the young contests, about 7,000 aged 12-17 from
137 countries and regions, "luck, records and medals".
</P>
<P>
"Not all of you will be winners. But, as the Olympic motto says
-- Victory is not important; the main thing is participation," the
president said.
</P>
<P>
The games started last Saturday but the opening ceremony was
put off to Monday so that ranking sports officials in France for
the World Cup soccer matches could arrive here on time and weary
fans could shift their attention to the Moscow events.
</P>
<P>
Three days into the games, six gold medals had been awarded,
four to Russian boys in the Greco-Roman wrestling matches. The
other two gold medalists were Yevangelos Zabrakas from Greece,
also in Greco-Roman wrestling, and Pawel Bonisch of Poland in
Fencing epee.
</P>
<P>
Monday night's gala at the Luzhniki Statium on the bank of
Moscow River and facing the picturesque Sparrow Hills repeatedly
drew the spectators' attention to Russia's past as a sports
powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic flame, brought in from Greece after a three-week
relay race, was passed on to the Mishutka bear cub, the games'
mascot, by 24 Russian Olympic gold medalists.
</P>
<P>
Today's Russia remains a formidable force in world sports and
it young athletes, totaling 210, are widely expected to grab the
most medals in the Youth Games.
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the gala have apparently succeeded in their
attempt to boost the national pride of Russians and to please most
foreign participants.
</P>
<P>
Cossacks on horseback and Eskimos riding dog-powered sleds were
featured along with performers from many other Russian regions
such as Volga and Ural.
</P>
<P>
After a countdown, the two huge panel displays in the stadium
shown footages of Russian cosmonauts greeting Muscovites and
participants of the games from the Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
As the extravaganza approached its climax, the sky over the
stadium started to clear up, thanks to the Russians'
state-of-the-art technology in dispersing the rain-laden clouds
over Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Six AN-12 and AN-30 planes took off hours before the start of
the opening ceremony to fulfil the task from an altitude of
6,000-8,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
The performances also featured cartoon figures of various
countries of the world, such as dragon-dancing Chinese,
bull-fighting Spaniards, snake-charming Indians and a Statue of
Liberty carried by Donald Duck. 
</P>
</TEXT>
