<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, July 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Clinton administration Monday asked Congress
for authority to waive sanctions just imposed on India and
Pakistan so that it could have more leverage in lessening harms on
U.S. business.
</P>
<P>
"Our purpose is not to punish for punishment's sake, but to
influence the behavior of both governments," Karl Inderfurth,
assistant secretary of state for South Asian affairs, told a
Senate hearing. "We do not wish for unnecessary harm to fall on
the civilian populations of either country... or on U.S.
businesses." (US-S.Asia-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said Monday that Japan remains
the key to Asia's recovery from a year-long financial crisis, and
that its policy of relying on Japan for the recovery also remains
intact despite the resignation of Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
"A healthy Japanese economy is critical for the Asia region and
for the global economy, and the United States will work on the
assumption that the new Japanese government will see that it is in
its own best interest to pursue economic reform expeditiously,"
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters.
(US-Japan-Hashimoto's Resignation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia will get a total of 11.2 billion U.S. dollars
from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in financial aid in
1998, an IMF high-ranking official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Director of the IMF's second European Department John
Odling-Smee told a press conference that about 5.6 billion U.S.
dollars will be provided to Russia immediately after its
government takes agreed-on steps. The second half of the aid
package, said Odling-Smee, will be available to the country by the
end of 1998. (Russia-IMF-Aid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The British army experts defused a 225-kilogram car
bomb outside a court house in the Northern Irish town of Newry on
Monday, police said.
</P>
<P>
An army bomb disposal expert dismantled the device in a
four-hour security operation after a telephoned warning. No group
had claimed responsibility so far, but police said dissident
republicans were believed to be behind the car bomb plot.
(UK-N. Ireland-Car Bomb)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash said Monday that
Turkey will retaliate if the Cypriot government finally deploys
S-300 missiles on the divided island, according to Turkish Cypriot
news agency TAK.
</P>
<P>
"Our position today stands at a point that you will get a
response to whatever you do," said Denktash in a meeting with a
Turkish Foreign Ministry delegation visiting the Turkish
Cypriots-controlled northern part of the Mediterranean island.
(Turkey-Cyprus-Russian Missile) 
</P>
