<HEADLINE> World Cup TV Ratings Low in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The 40-market overnight rating
for Sunday's World Cup final between Brazil and France was 46
percent lower than the Brazil-Italy final four years ago in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The big drop stems largely from the poor displays by the U.S.
soccer team and the limited attention paid to the world No. 1
sport by the Americans.
</P>
<P>
When the final national numbers are released, ABC should show
about a 50 percent drop in ratings for 12 games.
</P>
<P>
"We had realistic expectations for the World Cup, but we don't
only measure the success of the tournament by those numbers," said
ABC sports spokesman Mark Mandel.
</P>
<P>
A rating point for ABC represents 980,000 households. ABC and
ESPN were expected to show a modest profit on the 22 million U.S.
dollars TV right fees.
</P>
<P>
The 2002 World Cup is likely to see the rating drop even more
since the competitions in South Korea and Japan force earlier
starting times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
