<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Nonprofit Groups Turning to Cyberspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 13 (xinhua) -- Charities and other nonprofit
groups in the United States are turning to cyberspace to raise
money.
</P>
<P>
What attracts many nonprofit groups is the prospect of a cheap,
easy way to reach an estimated 57 million Americans with access to
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
Many nonprofits originally set up Web sites to spread their
mission and offer online activism. Now they are adding encryption
technology that makes it safer to send credit-card information
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Also, they use the techniques of electronic commerce to accept
online credit-card donations and conduct upscale auctions over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
The philanthropic spinoff of e-commerce is still in its
infancy; no one tracks how many nonprofits are fund-raising
online, or how many money they are bringing in. Yet a growing
number of nonprofits regard the Internet as a way to reduce their
reliance on expensive fund-raising methods like direct mail and
phone banking, according to Knight Ridder Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
GuideStar is a nonprofit online service that lists information
and financial data for 40,000 American charities and non-profit
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The trend has spawned a cottage industry of consultants and
companies that create or host secure Web sites for the non-profits
-- sometimes in exchange for a cut of the contributions.
</P>
<P>
CharityWeb, a California-based startup which has signed up
contracts with seven agencies, for instance, charges full
membership 99 U.S. dollars for setup, plus 2.5 percent to 5.5
percent per transaction.
</P>
<P>
The most successful online fund-raisers are philanthropy's
biggest brand names, such as the American Cancer Society and the
American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
The American Cancer Society began raising money in 1995 through
an online form that could be downloaded, then faxed or mailed.
This low-tech way trickled 3,000 dollars in each month. Online
contributions have grown fourfold since the nonprofit added secure
transactions to its Web site.
</P>
<P>
The American Red Cross launched online contributions in July
1996 and has raised about 128,000 dollars since then. During the
Midwest floods of 1997, contributions shot up to 300 monthly, up
from a more typical 25 to 40 per month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
