<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Scientists Develop Robot "Doctor" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- British scientists said Monday that
they have developed a robot "doctor" that can diagnose brain
cancer from reading complex scan results.
</P>
<P>
The computer program, which uses neural networks that model the
way the brain thinks, interprets patterns from a sophisticated
type of scanning technique called magnetic resonance spectroscopy
(MRS).
</P>
<P>
MRS scans, which can show the pattern of chemicals within
tumors, help doctors determine the type of brain tumor and how
severe the cancer is.
</P>
<P>
However, most doctors still prefer to diagnose and assess
tumors by conducting tests on surgically removed tissue sample
because the MRS scans are difficult to read.
</P>
<P>
With the new computer program, interpretation of the images and
graph from MRS scans becomes both automatic and objective. So far
the program has had an 80 percent success rate analyzing cancerous
tissue taken from patients.
</P>
<P>
"These results are very exciting as MRS could be a far better
way of diagnosing and assessing a tumor than a biopsy because it
does not involve surgery," Professor John Griffiths, of St George
Hospital Medical School in London, told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Griffiths and scientists from Britain's Cancer Research
Campaign have been working on the computer technique for the past
10 years. The program was designed by Dr Ross Maxwell, a former
researcher from the Cancer Research Campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
