<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Gov't to Inject 1.1 Billion Pounds into Science </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The British government Monday
unveiled plans to inject 1.1 billion pounds (1.8 billion U.S.
dollars) of new money into science and engineering with an aim to
upgrade the country's research infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the investment, Margaret Beckett, president of the
Board of Trade, said the money represented a "real vote of
confidence in Britain's scientists and engineers."
</P>
<P>
Much of the money, which will be available over a three-year
period, will go towards building or refurbishing laboratories at
universities. One-third of the cash will provide the research
councils with vital funds.
</P>
<P>
Four hundred million pounds (654.54 million dollars) was given
by the Wellcome Trust, the rest is from public funds, being
provided as part of the British government's Comprehensive
Spending Review, which is to be announced in full Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the new financial boost, the UK's science budget
will grow for each of the next three years from 1.34 billion
pounds (2.2 billion dollars) in 1998-1999 to 1.66 billion pounds
(2.72 billion dollars) in 2001-2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
