<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Tests Year 2000 Preparedness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street started Monday a
preliminary computer test on its preparedness for entering 2000,
without serious incident in the back offices for the first day.
</P>
<P>
In the first of two weeks of tests, 29 securities firms and 12
exchanges performed mock trades in an effort to determine how Wall
Street's vast computerized trading system will handle the
transition to year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the program said that the efforts were aimed at
ferreting out from members' communications systems signs of the
"year 2000 bug," which could cause computers that are set to read
only the last two digits of the year to malfunction or fail when
the calendar changes to 2000.
</P>
<P>
Experts have warned for years that many computers originally
programmed to recognize only the last two digits of a year will
fail on Jan. 1, 2000, when machines will assume it is 1900.
</P>
<P>
Some computers can be reprogrammed through tedious rewriting of
their software code, but many have embedded microchips that must
be physically replaced.
</P>
<P>
But other experts argued that such old fashioned computers are
rarely in use nowadays and people do not have to worry too much.
</P>
<P>
In back offices up and down Wall Street Monday, computers were
tricked into thinking it was December 29, 1999, and then asked to
execute hundreds of mock trades.
</P>
<P>
For the next two weeks, experts will monitor the changes of the
computer systems and performance of test trades in much smaller
quantities.
</P>
<P>
It is said that the securities industry will spend between 5
billion U.S. dollars and 6 billion U.S. dollars through 1999 to
fix the bug. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
