<HEADLINE> U.S. Seeks to Waive Sanctions on India, Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
Monday asked Congress for authority to waive sanctions just
imposed on India and Pakistan so that it could have more leverage
in lessening harms on U.S. business.
</P>
<P>
"Our purpose is not to punish for punishment's sake, but to
influence the behavior of both governments," Karl Inderfurth,
assistant secretary of state for South Asian affairs, told a
Senate hearing. "We do not wish for unnecessary harm to fall on
the civilian populations of either country... or on U.S.
businesses."
</P>
<P>
Inderfurth said, however, the sanctions won't be waived unless
"substantial progress" is made by India and Pakistan toward
nuclear nonproliferation goals.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration would like to see both India and
Pakistan agree to conduct no further nuclear tests, sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, refrain from attaching their
nuclear weapons to missiles, halt the production of weapons
material and seek peace in the disputed territory of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"These are steps we want to see both government take. They are
not demands.... Countries don't like to be dictated to," he told
the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on Near Eastern and
South Asian affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said leaders of both India and Pakistan had signaled a
willingness to talk about the situation in South Asia. "We will
not let our current momentum slip," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
