<HEADLINE> Russia Gets 11 Billion U.S. Dollars From IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia will get a total of 11.2
billion U.S. dollars from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) as
financial aid in 1998, an IMF high-ranking official said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Director of the IMF's second European Department John
Odling-Smee told a press conference that about 5.6 billion U.S.
dollars will be provided to Russia immediately after its
government takes agreed-on steps.
</P>
<P>
The second half of the aid package, said Odling-Smee, will be
available to the country by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the total amount of the aid to be provided by
the IMF by the end of the year to Russia will reach 12.5 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Odling-Smee meanwhile hailed a decision made by the Russian
government to ask the holders of treasury bonds (GKOs) to convert
them into medium- or long-term bonds denominated in U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He also praised the Russian government's determination to
reduce the budget deficit to 5.6 percent of GDP in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank also intends to provide 6 billion U.S. dollars
in 1998-1999 as investment and budget-substituting loans.
</P>
<P>
During the same period the Japanese government plans to give
1.5 billion U.S. dollars for supporting Russia's balance of
payments through co-financing World Bank loans for economic
restructuring, the Interfax news agency quoted head of the Moscow
office of the World Bank Michael Carter as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Chubais, the Kremlin's envoy to international financial
organizations, said Monday that the decision of the IMF and the
World Bank is unprecedented because of the changes that were made
in the procedure of decision-making to honor the Russian
government's request.
</P>
<P>
He noted the government's stabilization program provided the
basis for the talks with the IMF and the World Bank which approved
it as a document sufficient to guarantee the return of these
funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
