<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Core resources in the U.N.
development system should continue to come from the government
contributions of developed countries, a Chinese representative
told the U.N. Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The lack of core resources has led to the reduction in the
implementation of numerous assistance programs, seriously
undermining the interest of developing countries, said Yuan
Shaofu, representing China at an ECOSOC segment on operational
activities for international development.
</P>
<P>
"Without a strong sense of responsibility and political will,
no funding modality would be able to achieve the goal of
increasing resources," he noted.
</P>
<P>
China appreciates the efforts of the U.N. development system to
implement U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's reform initiatives,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Yuan said the U.N. resident coordinator should be the country
representative of a program to prevent the coordinator at the
country level from becoming anther layer of bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
Regarding private capital activities, Yuan said China agrees
that its complementary role should be fully intergrated, on the
condition that the nature of U.N. operational activities remains
unchanged. 
