<HEADLINE> Sino-Tanzanian Joint Venture of Farm Tools Formed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 13 (Xinhua) - The Tanzanian government and
a Chinese company, backed by the Chinese government, signed
Monday an agreement on establishing a joint venture to produce
farm tools.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania, through its Presidential Parastatal Sector Reform
Commission, and its partner, the Tianjin Machinery Import and
Export Corporation (Group) (TMG), will share the ownership and
operation of the assets of the defunct China-Tanzania Ubungo
Machinery Company Limited (CTU) by 30% and 70% respectively.
</P>
<P>
This ownership ratio reflects the contributions by the two
governments in setting up the Ubungo Farm Implements
Manufacturing Company Limited (UFI) at the Ubungo district in Dar
es Salaam, from which the CTU is born.
</P>
<P>
As part of the agreement, the TMG will take over the Chinese
government loans in the UFI and the Tanzanian government will be
absolved from its Chinese counterpart's loan which was used to
build up UFI over the past years.
</P>
<P>
Apart from making hoes, plows, machetes and other farm
products which were the main business of the UFI, the new CTU
will also make and trade in agricultural machinery, electrical
products and other engineering products.
</P>
<P>
"An investment plan, which is estimated at three million U.S.
Dollars, is earmarked for rehabilitating the factory and for
diversifying it into the new business areas," said the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations on the agreement began in 1996 following an
instruction by Chinese premier Zhu Rongji one year earlier when
he paid a visit to Tanzania, inspecting many of the Chinese-aided
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said joint ventures and cooperation would lead to restore
production and obtain sound economic benefits for the
money-losing enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"The TMG has enough confidence and actual strength to promote
the CTU into a good project gradually," said Li Shaoren, Vice
President of the TMG at the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1956, the TMG runs in the fields of farm tools'
manufacturing, scientific research, and importing and exporting.
</P>
<P>
It has set up six branches and eight representative offices in
the United States, Germany, Australia, Japan, Venezuela, Uganda,
Ethiopia, Hong Kong and other countries and regions all over the
world with more than one thousand regular customers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
