<HEADLINE> IMF, World Bank Support for Russia's Staggering Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Michel Camdessus, managing
director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), said Monday a
multibillion-dollar loan package for Russia and reforms by the
government would strengthen the country's fiscal position.
</P>
<P>
"The strengthening of Russia's economic policies -- both fiscal
and structural -- the large additional financial resources, and
the debt conversion scheme, should fundamentally improve the
financial situation of the Russian government," Camdessus said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Under the new economic program, Russia's fiscal position is
being strengthened markedly," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said he would recommend to the IMF executive board
that the lending agency provide Russia with 11.2 billion U.S.
dollars in 1998. He said half this amount (about 5.6 billion
dollars) would be provided "as soon as the agreed actions of the
Russian government have been taken, by legislation where
necessary, and upon IMF executive board approval."
</P>
<P>
The rest of the money would be made available later in the
year. Together with resources provided under an existing IMF loan
program with Russia, Camdessus said the total financing from the
IMF during the remainder of 1998 would come to 12.5 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"This support will help Russia face its difficult problems
which have been exacerbated by the sharp decline in commodity
prices, in particular oil," he said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF's executive board would consider the Russian
government's economic reform program on July 20.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the World Bank said it would provide up to 6 billion
dollars to Russia in 1998 and 1999 as part of the IMF rescue
package negotiated in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
"The World Bank stands ready with substantial financial support
to Russia for the implementation of this program and for
mitigating the severe social problems which the Russian people
currently face," World Bank President James Wolfensohn said in a
statement released in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"I am delighted the new Russian government has developed this
ambitious program of structural reform," noted the World Bank
chief. "Its implementation will send the clearest signals that
Russia's economic management is on track -- it should quickly
rebuild confidence and create the basis for the emergence in
Russia of the prosperity that we all want to see."
</P>
<P>
To support the IMF-led rescue, the World Bank said its board of
directors was expected to approve a 1.5 billion dollar structural
adjustment loan for Russia in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Under this loan, 800 million dollars would be made available in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Together with other planned disbursements, the World Bank said
total structural adjustment loan payments for Russia for the rest
of 1998 could reach 1.25 billion dollars. For 1999, the bank said
it planned to disburse 3 billion dollars in adjustment lending, so
long as Russia makes "strong progress" on economic reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
