leaders to abide by the decisions of the Independent Parades
Commission and to end this inflammatory situation, which has
provoked a week of violence," he said.
</P>
<P>
A decision by the commission to curtail one of the marches
prompted a week of violence as Protestant Orangemen demonstrated
for their right to carry out traditional parades through what are
now Catholic areas to commemorate 300-year-old British victories
over the native Irish.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to monitor closely the situation, and remain in
touch with British, Irish and Northern Ireland officials to help
in any way we can," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
The peace process in Northern Ireland was threatened as the
Protestants and Catholics renewed their conflict in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
In March, a peace plan was signed by the parties under the
auspices of the U.S., ending decades of conflict between the
pro-British Protestants and pro-Irish Catholics. 
