<HEADLINE> Civil Rights Leader Criticizes Supreme Court Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Supreme Court justices "should
be ashamed of themselves," Kweisi Mfume, president of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP), said
Monday, pointing to rulings on anti-affirmative action issues and
a lack of minority law clerks at the high court.
</P>
<P>
"The Supreme Court finds themselves as hypocrites when they
talk of diversity," The Associated Press quoted Mfume as saying in
an address to 3,000 NAACP members attending an annual meeting.
"They make decisions on affirmative action: what people can and
can't do in this society. But they just pontificate."
</P>
<P>
Mfume said that only seven of the 397 law clerks who work for
Supreme Court justices are of black ancestry and that no American
Indian has ever served in such a position.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Chief Justice William Rehnquist turned down
a request by minority lawyers to discuss the scarcity of minority
law clerks at the Supreme Court, saying he did not think such a
meeting "would serve any useful purpose."
</P>
<P>
The National Bar Association, which represents 17,000 black
attorneys, had extended the invitation to Rehnquist on behalf of a
coalition of minority bar association leaders.
</P>
<P>
The controversy was sparked by a published report that of the
clerks hired by all nine current justices, 1 percent were
Hispanic, 2 percent were black and 4.5 percent were
Asian-American.
</P>
<P>
Supreme Court spokeswoman Toni House said the court would have
no comment on Mfume's remarks.
</P>
<P>
Mfume, who handled the day-to-day operations of the largest
civil rights group in the country, said that until the justices do
a better job of integrating their own workplace, they shouldn't
issue decisions that roll back affirmative action and thereby
create less racially diverse work settings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980714.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Assists Jordan to Prepare Joining WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) has launched a 300,000 U.S. dollar
project in Jordan to promote its integration into the global
economy, UNDP announced here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The initiative will help the country prepare for upcoming
negotiations to join the World Trade Organization (WTO) by
training Jordanian negotiators, the U.N. segment said in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) is also
supporting the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
