<HEADLINE> GM Resumes Production at Three Assembly Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. No. 1 carmaker General
Motors Corp. resumed production at three assembly plants Monday,
as talks to end two strikes that have idled the most of GM's North
American production were stalled.
</P>
<P>
GM's chief negotiator, Vice President Gerald Knechtel, returned
to Detroit late Sunday, saying he was disappointed that weekend
talks had not resulted in a settlement as he had hoped, according
to an AP report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
However, there was a hint of progress at plant-level
negotiations. Talks lasted through Sunday night and into the early
morning hours at both plants before they were recessed. They were
to resume Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
GM had been pushing for a weekend settlement to coincide with
the end of the company's two-week summer vacation shutdown Monday.
The automaker reopened its Saturn car plant in Tennessee, its
truck plant in Oshawa, Ontario of Canada, and a small-car plant in
Ramos Arizpe, Mexico, -- the only ones unaffected so far by the
strike.
</P>
<P>
GM's 26 other major assembly plants in North America will
remain closed, along with more than 100 parts plants. In addition
to 9,200 striking workers, about 162,000 other workers have been
idled.
</P>
<P>
Losses totaled nearly 1.2 billion U.S. dollars before the
company began its previously scheduled vacation shutdown on June
29. Losses of between 75 million dollars and 80 million dollars a
day will begin piling up again Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
